{"title_page": "Jaws (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1975 American horror-thriller film directed by Steven Spielberg}}\n{{Other uses|Jaws (disambiguation){{!}}Jaws}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Jaws\n| image          = JAWS Movie poster.jpg\n| alt            = Movie poster shows a woman in the ocean swimming to the right. Below her is a large shark, and only its head and open mouth with teeth can be seen. Within the image is the film's title and above it in a surrounding black background is the phrase \"The most terrifying motion picture from the terrifying No. 1 best seller.\" The bottom of the image details the starring actors and lists credits and the MPAA rating.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster by [[Roger Kastel]]\n| director       = [[Steven Spielberg]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Richard D. Zanuck]]\n* [[David Brown (producer)|David Brown]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Peter Benchley]]\n* [[Carl Gottlieb]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Jaws (novel)|Jaws]]''|Peter Benchley}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Roy Scheider]]\n* [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]]\n* [[Richard Dreyfuss]]\n* [[Lorraine Gary]]\n* [[Murray Hamilton]]\n}}\n| music          = [[John Williams]]\n| cinematography = [[Bill Butler (cinematographer)|Bill Butler]]\n| editing        = [[Verna Fields]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* Zanuck/Brown Company<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetailsPrintView/55193|title=Jaws (1975)|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Universal Pictures]]<ref name =afi/>\n}}\n| distributor    = Universal Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1975|06|20}}\n| runtime        = 124 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 124:01--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/jaws-3 | title=''JAWS'' (A) | publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=June 12, 1975 | accessdate=June 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $9 million<!-- Do not change the budget to the Box Office Mojo figure. The producer confirmed the film cost $9 million. This is sourced in the main article. -->\n| gross          = $470.7 million\n}}\n'''''Jaws''''' is a 1975 American <!-- THE CONSENSUS IS TO LIST JAWS AS A \"THRILLER\"; DO NOT CHANGE IT WITHOUT OBTAINING A NEW CONSENSUS ON THE TALK PAGE-->[[thriller film]] directed by [[Steven Spielberg]] and based on [[Peter Benchley]]'s 1974 [[Jaws (novel)|novel of the same name]]. In the film, a [[great white shark|man-eating great white]] shark attacks beachgoers at a summer [[resort town]], prompting police chief [[Martin Brody]] ([[Roy Scheider]]) to hunt it with the help of a [[Marine biology|marine biologist]] ([[Richard Dreyfuss]]) and a professional shark hunter ([[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]]). [[Murray Hamilton]] plays the mayor, and [[Lorraine Gary]] portrays Brody's wife. The screenplay is credited to Benchley, who wrote the first drafts, and actor-writer [[Carl Gottlieb]], who rewrote the script during [[principal photography]].\n\nShot mostly on location on [[Martha's Vineyard]] in [[Massachusetts]], ''Jaws'' had a troubled production, going over budget and past schedule. As the art department's mechanical sharks often malfunctioned, Spielberg decided to mostly suggest the shark's presence, employing an ominous and minimalist theme created by composer [[John Williams]] to indicate its impending appearances. Spielberg and others have compared this suggestive approach to that of director [[Alfred Hitchcock]]. [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]] gave the film what was then an exceptionally [[wide release]] for a [[Major film studio|major studio]] picture, on over 450 screens, accompanied by an extensive marketing campaign with a heavy emphasis on television spots and tie-in merchandise.\n\nConsidered one of [[List of films considered the best|the greatest films ever made]], ''Jaws'' was the prototypical summer [[Blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]], regarded as a watershed moment in motion picture history, and it won several awards for its music and editing. It was the [[Timeline of highest-grossing films|highest-grossing film]] until the release of ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' in 1977. Both films were pivotal in establishing the modern Hollywood business model, which pursues high box-office returns from action and adventure films with simple [[high-concept]] premises, released during the summer in thousands of theaters and heavily advertised. ''Jaws'' was followed by [[Jaws (franchise)|three sequels]], all without Spielberg or Benchley, and many imitative thrillers. In 2001, it was selected by the [[Library of Congress]] for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]] as \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please review WP:FILMPLOT before adding material. Plot summaries, usually for popular films, are set between 400-700 words. -->\nDuring a beach party at dusk on Amity Island, a young woman, Chrissie Watkins, goes [[nude swimming|skinny dipping]] in the ocean. While [[treading water]], she is violently pulled under. The next day, her partial remains are found on shore. The medical examiner's ruling that the death was due to a [[shark attack]] leads police chief Martin Brody to close the beaches. Mayor Larry Vaughn overrules him, fearing that the town's summer economy will be ruined and points out that the town has never had trouble with sharks. The coroner now concurs with the mayor's theory that Chrissie was killed in a boating accident. Brody reluctantly accepts their conclusion until another fatal shark attack occurs shortly thereafter, with the shark killing a young boy paddling on his raft in full daylight on a crowded beach. A $3000 bounty is placed on the shark by his grieving mother, prompting an amateur shark-hunting frenzy. Local professional shark hunter Quint offers his services for $10,000. Meanwhile, consulting oceanographer Matt Hooper examines Chrissie's remains, and confirms her death was caused by a shark\u2014an unusually large one rare to Amity's waters.\n\nWhen local fishermen catch a [[tiger shark]], the mayor proclaims the beaches safe. Hooper however disputes that it is the same predator, confirming this after no human remains are found inside it. Hooper and Brody find a half-sunken vessel while searching the night waters in Hooper's boat. Underwater, Hooper retrieves a sizable [[great white shark]]'s tooth embedded in the submerged hull. He drops it in fright after encountering the partial corpse of local fisherman Ben Gardner. Vaughn discounts Brody and Hooper's statements that a huge great white shark is responsible for the deaths, and refuses to close the beaches, allowing only added safety precautions. On the Fourth of July weekend, tourists pack the beaches. Following a juvenile prank in which the presence of a shark is simulated, the real shark sneaks through and enters a nearby [[estuary]], killing a boater and causing Brody's oldest son, Michael, to go into shock. Brody then convinces Vaughn to hire Quint to kill the shark.\n\nQuint, Brody, and Hooper set out on Quint's boat, the ''Orca'', to hunt the shark. While Brody lays down a [[Chumming|chum]] line, Quint waits for an opportunity to hook the shark. Without warning, it appears behind the boat. Quint, estimating its length at {{convert|25|ft|m}} and weight at {{convert|3|t}}, harpoons it with a line attached to a flotation barrel, but the shark pulls the barrel underwater and disappears.\n\nAt nightfall, Quint and Hooper drunkenly exchange stories about their assorted scars, and Quint reveals that he survived the [[USS Indianapolis (CA-35)|USS ''Indianapolis'']]. The shark returns unexpectedly, ramming the boat's hull, and disabling the power. The men work through the night, repairing the engine. In the morning, Brody attempts to call the Coast Guard, but Quint, who has become obsessed with killing the shark without outside assistance, smashes the radio. After a long chase, Quint harpoons another barrel into the shark. The line is tied to the stern cleats, but the shark drags the boat backward, swamping the deck and flooding the engine compartment. Quint prepares to sever the line to prevent the transom from being pulled out but the cleats break off, keeping the barrels attached to the shark. Quint heads toward shore to draw the shark into shallower waters, but he pushes the damaged engine past the safety limits and the overtaxed engine fails.\n\nWith the ''Orca'' slowly sinking, the trio attempt a riskier approach. Hooper puts on [[Scuba set|scuba gear]] and enters the water in a [[shark-proof cage]], intending to lethally inject the shark with [[strychnine]], using a hypodermic spear. The shark attacks the cage, causing Hooper to drop the spear, which sinks and is lost. While the shark thrashes in the tangled remains of the cage, Hooper manages to escape to the seabed. The shark escapes and leaps onto the sinking deck of the boat, dragging Quint down and devouring him. Trapped on the sinking vessel, Brody jams a pressurized scuba tank into the shark's mouth, and, climbing the crow's nest, shoots the tank with a rifle. The resulting explosion obliterates the shark and then sinks to the bottom. Hooper surfaces, and he and Brody paddle back to Amity Island clinging to the remaining barrels.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n[[Richard D. Zanuck]] and [[David Brown (producer)|David Brown]], producers at [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]], independently heard about Peter Benchley's novel ''[[Jaws (novel)|Jaws]]''. Brown came across it in the literature section of lifestyle magazine ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', then edited by his wife, [[Helen Gurley Brown]]. A small card written by the magazine's book editor gave a detailed description of the plot, concluding with the comment \"might make a good movie\".<ref name=\"Prigg\u00e96\">{{harvnb|Prigg\u00e9|2004|p=6}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Scanlon|2009|p=197}}</ref> The producers each read the book over the course of a single night and agreed the next morning that it was \"the most exciting thing that they had ever read\" and that they wanted to produce a film version, although they were unsure how it would be accomplished.<ref name=jawschap1>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"From Novel to Script\"}}</ref> They purchased the film rights in 1973, before the book's publication, for approximately $175,000 (equivalent to $990,000 in 2018).<ref name=\"Brode 50\">{{harvnb|Brode|1995|p=50}}</ref> Brown claimed that if had they read the book twice, they would never have made the film because they would have realized how difficult it would be to execute certain sequences.<ref name=\"McBride 231\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=231}}</ref>\n\nTo direct, Zanuck and Brown first considered veteran filmmaker [[John Sturges]]\u2014whose r\u00e9sum\u00e9 included another maritime adventure, ''[[The Old Man and the Sea (1958 film)|The Old Man and the Sea]]''\u2014before offering the job to [[Dick Richards]], whose directorial debut, ''[[The Culpepper Cattle Co.]]'' had come out the previous year.<ref name=\"McBride232\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=232}}</ref> However, they grew irritated by Richards's habit of describing the shark as a whale and soon dropped him from the project.<ref name=\"McBride232\"/> Meanwhile, [[Steven Spielberg]] very much wanted the job. The 26-year-old had just directed his first theatrical film, ''[[The Sugarland Express]]'', for Zanuck and Brown. At the end of a meeting in their office, Spielberg noticed their copy of the still-unpublished Benchley novel, and after reading it was immediately captivated.<ref name=\"Brode 50\"/> He later observed that it was similar to his 1971 television film ''[[Duel (1971 film)|Duel]]'' in that both deal with \"these leviathans targeting [[everyman|everymen]]\".<ref name=jawschap1/> He also revealed in \"The Making of ''Jaws''\" documentary on the 2012 DVD release that he directly referenced ''Duel'' by repurposing the sound of the truck being destroyed as the death roar of the shark. After Richards's departure, the producers signed Spielberg to direct in June 1973, before the release of ''The Sugarland Express''.<ref name=\"McBride232\"/>\n\nBefore production began, however, Spielberg grew reluctant to continue with ''Jaws'', in fear of becoming [[Typecasting (acting)|typecast]] as the \"truck and shark director\".<ref name=biskind264/> He wanted to move over to [[20th Century Fox]]'s ''[[Lucky Lady]]'' instead, but Universal exercised its right under its contract with the director to veto his departure.<ref name=\"McBride240\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=240}}</ref> Brown helped convince Spielberg to stick with the project, saying that \"after [''Jaws''], you can make all the films you want\".<ref name=biskind264/> The film was given an estimated budget of $3.5&nbsp;million and a shooting schedule of 55&nbsp;days. [[Principal photography]] was set to begin in May 1974. Universal wanted the shoot to finish by the end of June, when the major studios' contract with the [[Screen Actors Guild]] was due to expire, to avoid any disruptions due to a potential strike.<ref>{{harvnb|Gottlieb|2005|p=52}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nFor the screen adaptation, Spielberg wanted to stay with the novel's basic plot, but discarded many of Benchley's [[subplot]]s.<ref name=\"Brode 50\"/> He declared that his favorite part of the book was the shark hunt on the last 120&nbsp;pages, and told Zanuck when he accepted the job, \"I'd like to do the picture if I could change the first two acts and base the first two acts on original screenplay material, and then be very true to the book for the last third.\"{{sfn|Friedman|Notbohm|2000|p=8}} When the producers purchased the rights to his novel, they promised Benchley that he could write the first draft of the [[screenplay]].<ref name=\"Brode 50\"/> The intent was to make sure a script could be done despite an impending threat of a [[Writers Guild of America, West|Writer's Guild]] strike, given Benchley was not unionized.<ref name=empire>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1516| title=Jaws: The Oral History|work=Empire|author1=Mark Salisbury |author2=Ian Nathan |accessdate=March 23, 2015}}</ref> Overall, he wrote three drafts before the script was turned over to other writers;<ref name=\"Brode 50\"/> delivering his final version to Spielberg, he declared, \"I'm written out on this, and that's the best I can do.\"<ref name=inside_story/> Benchley would later describe his contribution to the finished film as \"the storyline and the ocean stuff \u2013 basically, the mechanics\", given he \"didn't know how to put the character texture into a screenplay.\"<ref name=empire/> One of his changes was to remove the novel's adulterous affair between Ellen Brody and Matt Hooper, at the suggestion of Spielberg, who feared it would compromise the camaraderie between the men on the ''Orca''.<ref name=int11/> During the film's production, Benchley agreed to return and play a small onscreen role as a reporter.<ref name=\"jawschap3\"/>\n\nSpielberg, who felt that the characters in Benchley's script were still unlikable, invited the young screenwriter [[John Byrum]] to do a rewrite, but he declined the offer.<ref name=biskind264>{{harvnb|Biskind|1998|p=264}}</ref>\n''[[Columbo]]'' creators [[William Link]] and [[Richard Levinson]] also declined Spielberg's invitation.<ref name=\"McBride238\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=238}}</ref> [[Tony Award|Tony]] and [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning [[playwright]] [[Howard Sackler]] was in Los Angeles when the filmmakers began looking for another writer and offered to do an uncredited rewrite; since the producers and Spielberg were unhappy with Benchley's drafts, they quickly agreed.<ref name=jawschap1/> At the suggestion of Spielberg, Brody's characterization made him afraid of water, \"coming from an urban jungle to find something more terrifying off this placid island near Massachusetts.\"<ref name=empire/>\n\nSpielberg wanted \"some levity\" in ''Jaws'', humor that would avoid making it \"a dark sea hunt\", so he turned to his friend [[Carl Gottlieb]], a comedy writer-actor then working on the sitcom ''[[The Odd Couple (1970 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]''.<ref name=inside_story/> Spielberg sent Gottlieb a script, asking what the writer would change and if there was a role he would be interested in performing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omaha.com/article/20100520/ENTERTAINMENT/705209910|title=Bob's Take: 'Jaws' script doctor ruthless to character played by him|first=Bob|last=Fischbach|work=[[Omaha World-Herald]]|date=May 20, 2010|accessdate=March 6, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523064031/http://www.omaha.com/article/20100520/ENTERTAINMENT/705209910|archivedate=May 23, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Gottlieb sent Spielberg three pages of notes, and picked the part of Meadows, the politically connected editor of the local paper. He passed the audition one week before Spielberg took him to meet the producers regarding a writing job.<ref name=Baer198/>\n\nWhile the deal was initially for a \"one-week dialogue polish\", Gottlieb eventually became the primary screenwriter, rewriting the entire script during a nine-week period of principal photography.<ref name=Baer198>{{harvnb|Baer|2008|p=198}}</ref> The script for each scene was typically finished the night before it was shot, after Gottlieb had dinner with Spielberg and members of the cast and crew to decide what would go into the film. Many pieces of dialogue originated from the actors' improvisations during these meals; a few were created on set, most notably Roy Scheider's [[ad-lib]] of the line \"You're gonna need a bigger boat.\"<ref name=Baer>{{harvnb|Baer|2008|pages=201\u2013202}}</ref> [[John Milius]] contributed dialogue polishes,<ref name=Friedman167/> and ''Sugarland Express'' writers [[Matthew Robbins (screenwriter)|Matthew Robbins]] and [[Hal Barwood]] also made uncredited contributions.<ref name=biskind265>{{harvnb|Biskind|1998|p=265}}</ref> Spielberg has claimed that he prepared his own draft, although it is unclear to what degree the other screenwriters drew on his material.<ref name=Friedman167/> One specific alteration he called for in the story was to change the cause of the shark's death from extensive wounds to a scuba tank explosion, as he felt audiences would respond better to a \"big rousing ending\".<ref name=jawschap11>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Climax\"}}</ref> The director estimated the final script had a total of 27 scenes that were not in the book.<ref name=int11>{{harvnb|Friedman|Notbohm|2000|pages=11\u201312}}</ref>\n\nBenchley had written ''Jaws'' after reading about sport fisherman [[Frank Mundus]]'s capture of an enormous shark in 1964. According to Gottlieb, Quint was loosely based on Mundus, whose book ''Sportfishing for Sharks'' he read for research.<ref name=baer209/> Sackler came up with the backstory of Quint as a survivor of the World War II {{USS|Indianapolis|CA-35|6}} disaster.<ref name=aicn/> The question of who deserves the most credit for writing Quint's monologue about the ''Indianapolis'' has caused substantial controversy. Spielberg described it as a collaboration between Sackler, Milius, and actor [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]], who was also a playwright.<ref name=\"Friedman167\">{{harvnb|Friedman|2006|p=167}}</ref> According to the director, Milius turned Sackler's \"three-quarters of a page\" speech into a monologue, and that was then rewritten by Shaw.<ref name=aicn/> Gottlieb gives primary credit to Shaw, downplaying Milius's contribution.<ref name=\"Gottlieb208\">{{harvnb|Gottlieb|2005|p=208}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Jankiewicz |first1=Patrick |title=Just When You Thought It Was Safe: A Jaws Companion |publisher=BearManor Media |location=Duncan, OK |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eqY-DwAAQBAJ&q=+Indianapolis#v=snippet&q=Indianapolis |accessdate=June 29, 2018|year=2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n{| class=\"infobox\"\n|-\n! Actor\n! class=\"unsortable\" |<!--non-semantic mimicry of film credit look -->\n! Role <!-- or \"Character\" -->\n|-\n| {{sortname|Roy|Scheider}}\n|\n| Chief Martin Brody\n|-\n| {{sortname|Robert|Shaw|Robert Shaw (actor)}}\n|\n| Quint\n|-\n| {{sortname|Richard|Dreyfuss}}\n|\n| Matt Hooper\n|-\n| {{sortname|Lorraine|Gary}}\n|\n| Ellen Brody\n|-\n| {{sortname|Murray|Hamilton}}\n|\n| Mayor Larry Vaughn\n|-\n| {{sortname|Carl|Gottlieb}}\n|\n| Meadows\n|-\n| {{sortname|Jeffrey|Kramer}}\n|\n| Deputy Hendricks\n|-\n| {{sortname|Susan|Backlinie}}\n|\n| Chrissie Watkins\n|-\n| {{sortname|Peter|Benchley}}\n|\n| Interviewer\n|}\nThough Spielberg complied with a request from Zanuck and Brown to cast known actors,<ref name=jawschap3/> he wanted to avoid hiring any big stars. He felt that \"somewhat anonymous\" performers would help the audience \"believe this was happening to people like you and me\", whereas \"stars bring a lot of memories along with them, and those memories can sometimes&nbsp;... corrupt the story.\"<ref name=biskind265/> The director added that in his plans \"the superstar was gonna be the shark\".<ref name=inside_story>{{Cite video | people = Pangolin Pictures| title = Jaws: The Inside Story | medium = Television documentary | publisher = [[The Biography Channel]] | date = June 16, 2010}}</ref> The first actors cast were [[Lorraine Gary]], the wife of then-president of Universal [[Sid Sheinberg]], as Ellen Brody,<ref name=jawschap3>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Casting \"}}</ref> and [[Murray Hamilton]] as the mayor of Amity Island.<ref>{{harvnb|Gottlieb|2005|p=56}}</ref> Stuntwoman-turned-actress [[Susan Backlinie]] was cast as Chrissie (the first victim) as she knew how to swim and was willing to perform nude.<ref name=inside_story/> Most minor roles were played by residents of [[Martha's Vineyard]], where the film was shot. One example was Deputy Hendricks, played by future television producer [[Jeffrey Kramer]].{{sfn|Nadler|2006|p=35}} [[Lee Fierro]] plays Mrs. Kintner, the mother of the shark's second victim Alex Kintner (played by Jeffrey Voorhees).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moreau |first1=Jordan |title=Lee Fierro, \u2018Jaws\u2019 Actor, Dies of Coronavirus at 91 |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/lee-fierro-jaws-dead-dies-coronavirus-1234571541/ |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=Variety |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe role of Brody was offered to [[Robert Duvall]], but the actor was interested only in portraying Quint.<ref name=\"McBride237\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=237}}</ref> [[Charlton Heston]] expressed a desire for the role, but Spielberg felt that Heston would bring a screen persona too grand for the part of a police chief of a modest community.<ref>{{harvnb|McBride|1999|pp=236\u2013237}}</ref> [[Roy Scheider]] became interested in the project after overhearing Spielberg at a party talk with a screenwriter about having the shark jump up onto a boat.<ref name=\"jawschap3\"/> Spielberg was initially apprehensive about hiring Scheider, fearing he would portray a \"tough guy\", similar to his role in ''[[The French Connection (film)|The French Connection]]''.<ref name=\"McBride237\"/>\n\nNine days before the start of production, neither Quint nor Hooper had been cast.<ref name=baer206>{{harvnb|Baer|2008|p=206}}</ref> The role of Quint was originally offered to actors [[Lee Marvin]] and [[Sterling Hayden]], both of whom passed.<ref name=jawschap3/><ref name=\"McBride237\"/> Zanuck and Brown had just finished working with Robert Shaw on ''[[The Sting]]'', and suggested him to Spielberg.<ref name=\"Jackson20\"/> Shaw was reluctant to take the role since he did not like the book, but decided to accept at the urging of both his wife, actress [[Mary Ure]], and his secretary\u2014\"The last time they were that enthusiastic was ''[[From Russia with Love (film)|From Russia with Love]]''. And they were right.\"<ref name=time>{{cite journal|title=Summer of the Shark |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130202256/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C913189-1%2C00.html |archivedate=November 30, 2009 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,913189-1,00.html |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=June 23, 1975 |accessdate=November 9, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Shaw based his performance on fellow cast member Craig Kingsbury, a local fisherman, farmer, and legendary eccentric, who was playing fisherman Ben Gardner.{{sfn|Nadler|2006|p=36}} Spielberg described Kingsbury as \"the purest version of who, in my mind, Quint was\", and some of his offscreen utterances were incorporated into the script as lines of Gardner and Quint.<ref name=jawschap5/> Another source for some of Quint's dialogue and mannerisms, especially in the third act at sea, was Vineyard mechanic and boat-owner Lynn Murphy.<ref name=vingaz>{{cite news|url=http://vineyardgazette.com/news/2011/05/26/once-bitten-islanders-reveal-more-jaws|author=Brannen, Peter|accessdate=July 7, 2015|newspaper=[[Vineyard Gazette]]|date=May 26, 2011|title=Once Bitten: Islanders Reveal More ''Jaws''}}</ref><ref name=\"Taylor250\">{{harvnb|Taylor|2012|pp=250\u2013251}}</ref>\n\nFor the role of Hooper, Spielberg initially wanted [[Jon Voight]].<ref name=\"Jackson20\">{{harvnb|Jackson|2007|p=20}}</ref> [[Timothy Bottoms]], [[Joel Grey]], and [[Jeff Bridges]] were also considered for the part.<ref name=\"McBride236\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=236}}</ref> Spielberg's friend [[George Lucas]] suggested [[Richard Dreyfuss]], whom he had directed in ''[[American Graffiti]]''.<ref name=jawschap3/> The actor initially passed, but changed his decision after he attended a pre-release screening of ''[[The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz (film)|The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz]]'', which he had just completed. Disappointed in his performance and fearing that no one would want to hire him once ''Kravitz'' was released, he immediately called Spielberg and accepted the role in ''Jaws''. Because the film the director envisioned was so dissimilar to Benchley's novel, Spielberg asked Dreyfuss not to read it.<ref name=\"Roan30Years\">{{cite news|last=Harvey|first=Neil|work=[[The Roanoke Times]]|title=30 years of 'Jaws'|url=http://www.roanoke.com/extra%5C25348.html|date=June 13, 2005|accessdate=March 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130104132211/http://www.roanoke.com/extra%5C25348.html|archivedate=January 4, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> As a result of the casting, Hooper was rewritten to better suit the actor,<ref name=baer206/> as well as to be more representative of Spielberg, who came to view Dreyfuss as his \"[[alter ego]]\".<ref name=\"McBride236\"/>\n\n===Filming===\n{{quote box|width=30em|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|quote=We started the film without a script, without a cast and without a shark.|source=\u2014actor [[Richard Dreyfuss]] on the film's troubled production<ref name=\"SharkTale\"/>}}\n\n[[Principal photography]] began May 2, 1974,<ref name=\"McBride233\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=233}}</ref> on the island of [[Martha's Vineyard]], Massachusetts, selected after consideration was given to eastern [[Long Island]]. Brown explained later that the production \"needed a vacation area that was lower middle class enough so that an appearance of a shark would destroy the tourist business.\"<ref name=\"Prigg\u00e97\">{{harvnb|Prigg\u00e9|2004|p=7}}</ref> Martha's Vineyard was also chosen because the surrounding ocean had a sandy bottom that never dropped below {{Convert|35|ft}} for {{convert|12|mi}} out from shore, which allowed the mechanical sharks to operate while also beyond sight of land.<ref name=jawschap4>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Location\"}}</ref> As Spielberg wanted to film the aquatic sequences relatively close-up to resemble what people see while swimming, cinematographer [[Bill Butler (cinematographer)|Bill Butler]] devised new equipment to facilitate marine and underwater shooting, including a rig to keep the camera stable regardless of tide and a sealed submersible camera box.<ref>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Photographing Jaws\"}}</ref> Spielberg asked the art department to avoid red in both scenery and wardrobe, so that the blood from the attacks would be the only red element and cause a bigger shock.<ref name=jawschap5/>\n[[File:Menemsha.jpg|thumb|left|The fishing village of [[Menemsha, Massachusetts|Menemsha]], Martha's Vineyard, was the primary location.<ref name=Gottlieb92>{{harvnb|Gottlieb|2005|p=92}}</ref>|alt=Fishing cottages and boats on Menemsha's harbor.]]\nInitally the films producers wanted to train a Great White shark<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edfilmfest.org.uk/latest/10-things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-jaws|title=10 Things You Probably Didn't Know About JAWS {{!}} Edinburgh International Film Festival|website=www.edfilmfest.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> but quickly realized this wasn't possible so three full-size [[Pneumatics|pneumatically]] powered prop sharks\u2014which the film crew nicknamed \"Bruce\" after Spielberg's lawyer, Bruce Ramer\u2014were made for the production:<ref name=\"McBride241\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=241}}</ref> a \"sea-sled shark\", a full-body prop with its belly missing that was towed with a {{convert|300|ft|adj=on}} line, and two \"platform sharks\", one that moved from camera-left to -right (with its hidden left side exposing an array of pneumatic hoses), and an opposite model with its right flank uncovered.<ref name=\"Brode 50\"/> The sharks were designed by art director [[Joe Alves]] during the third quarter of 1973. Between November 1973 and April 1974, the sharks were fabricated at Rolly Harper's Motion Picture & Equipment Rental in [[Sun Valley, Los Angeles|Sun Valley, California]]. Their construction involved a team of as many as 40 effects technicians, supervised by mechanical effects supervisor [[Bob Mattey]], best known for creating the giant squid in ''[[20,000 Leagues Under the Sea (1954 film)|20,000 Leagues Under the Sea]]''. After the sharks were completed, they were trucked to the shooting location.<ref name=jawschap6>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"The Shark\"}}</ref> In early July, the platform used to tow the two side-view sharks capsized as it was being lowered to the ocean floor, forcing a team of divers to retrieve it.<ref name=jawschap7>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"The Shark Is Not Working\"}}</ref> The model required 14 operators to control all of the moving parts.<ref name=\"Roan30Years\"/>\n\n''Jaws'' was the first major motion picture to be shot on the ocean,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainmentvoice.com/2017/10/07/hbo-spielberg-documentary-is-an-unabashed-love-letter-to-a-film-lover/|title=HBO's 'Spielberg' Documentary Is an Unabashed Love Letter to a Film Lover|last=Sokol|first=Tony|access-date=October 8, 2017|url-status=}}</ref> resulting in a troubled shoot, and went far over budget. David Brown said that the budget \"was $4&nbsp;million and the picture wound up costing $9&nbsp;million\";<ref name=\"Prigg\u00e98\">{{harvnb|Prigg\u00e9|2004|p=8}}</ref> the effects outlays alone grew to $3 million due to the problems with the mechanical sharks.<ref name=colrad/> Disgruntled crew members gave the film the nickname \"Flaws\".<ref name=\"Roan30Years\"/><ref name=\"McBride241\"/> Spielberg attributed many problems to his perfectionism and his inexperience. The former was epitomized by his insistence on shooting at sea with a life-sized shark; \"I could have shot the movie in the tank or even in a protected lake somewhere, but it would not have looked the same,\" he said.<ref name=time/> As for his lack of experience: \"I was naive about the ocean, basically. I was pretty naive about mother nature and the hubris of a filmmaker who thinks he can conquer the elements was foolhardy, but I was too young to know I was being foolhardy when I demanded that we shoot the film in the Atlantic Ocean and not in a North Hollywood tank.\"<ref name=aicn>{{cite web|url=http://www.aintitcool.com/node/49921|author=Vespe, Eric (Quint)|accessdate=January 2, 2012|publisher=[[Ain't It Cool News]]|date=June 6, 2011|title=Steven Spielberg and Quint have an epic chat all about JAWS as it approaches its 36th Anniversary!}}</ref> Gottlieb said that \"there was nothing to do except make the movie\", so everyone kept overworking, and while as a writer he did not have to attend the ocean set every day, once the crewmen returned they arrived \"ravaged and sunburnt, windblown and covered with salt water\".<ref name=empire/>\n\nShooting at sea led to many delays: unwanted sailboats drifted into frame, cameras got soaked,<ref name=jawschap5/> and the ''Orca'' once began to sink with the actors on board.<ref>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"The ''Orca''\"}}</ref> The prop sharks frequently malfunctioned owing to a series of problems including bad weather, pneumatic hoses taking on salt water, frames fracturing due to water resistance, corroding skin, and [[electrolysis]]. From the first water test onward, the \"non-absorbent\" neoprene foam that made up the sharks' skin soaked up liquid, causing the sharks to balloon, and the sea-sled model frequently got entangled among forests of seaweed.<ref name=time/><ref name=jawschap7/> Spielberg later calculated that during the 12-hour daily work schedule, on average only four hours were actually spent filming.<ref>{{harvnb|Sinyard|1989|p=31}}</ref> Gottlieb was nearly decapitated by the boat's propellers, and Dreyfuss was almost imprisoned in the steel cage.<ref name=time/> The actors were frequently [[seasickness|seasick]]. Shaw also fled to Canada whenever he could due to tax problems,{{sfn|Nadler|2006|p=36-37}} engaged in [[binge drinking]], and developed a grudge against Dreyfuss, who was getting rave reviews for his performance in ''Duddy Kravitz''.<ref name=inside_story/><ref>{{cite interview |last=Dreyfuss |first=Richard |subject-link=Richard Dreyfuss |interviewer=Steven Bratter |title=Tension Between Richard Dreyfuss and Robert Shaw in \"JAWS\" |date=December 6, 2012 |publisher=[[University of Copenhagen]] |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v8Ny_NU68ow |access-date=June 6, 2015}}</ref> Editor [[Verna Fields]] rarely had material to work with during principal photography, as according to Spielberg \"we would shoot five scenes in a good day, three in an average day, and none in a bad day.\"<ref>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Verna Field 'Mother Cutter'\"}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mechashark.JPG|thumb|alt=A large model shark is hoisted by a crane as two men watch it.|The mechanical shark, attached to the tower]]\nThe delays proved beneficial in some regards. The script was refined during production, and the unreliable mechanical sharks forced Spielberg to shoot many scenes so that the shark was only hinted at. For example, for much of the shark hunt, its location is indicated by the floating yellow barrels.<ref name=\"Sinyard36\"/> The opening had the shark devouring Chrissie,<ref name=inside_story/> but it was rewritten so that it would be shot with Backlinie being dragged and yanked by cables to simulate an attack.<ref name=jawschap5>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Production Stories\"}}</ref> Spielberg also included multiple shots of just the dorsal fin. This forced restraint is widely thought to have added to the film's suspense.<ref name=\"Sinyard36\">{{harvnb|Sinyard|1989|p=36}}</ref> As Spielberg put it years later, \"The film went from a Japanese Saturday matinee horror flick to more of a [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock]], the less-you-see-the-more-you-get thriller.\"<ref name=\"Roan30Years\"/> In another interview, he similarly declared, \"The shark not working was a godsend. It made me become more like Alfred Hitchcock than like [[Ray Harryhausen]].\" The acting became crucial for making audiences believe in such a big shark: \"The more fake the shark looked in the water, the more my anxiety told me to heighten the naturalism of the performances.\"<ref name=aicn/>\n\nFootage of real sharks was shot by [[Ron and Valerie Taylor]] in the waters off [[Dangerous Reef]] in [[South Australia]], with a short actor in a miniature shark cage to create the illusion that the sharks were enormous.<ref name=AdelaideNow>{{cite news|last1=Davies|first1=Nathan|title=How a big shark and a little man forced Spielberg to make Jaws even better|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/how-a-big-shark-and-a-little-man-forced-spielberg-to-make-jaws-even-better/news-story/7ea6e7b7d12b5c680a1afd545fc9a1ca|accessdate=January 21, 2016|newspaper=The Advertiser|date=June 19, 2015}}</ref> During the Taylors' shoot, a great white attacked the boat and cage. The footage of the cage attack was so stunning that Spielberg was eager to incorporate it in the film. No one had been in the cage at the time, however, and the script, following the novel, originally had the shark killing Hooper in it. The storyline was consequently altered to have Hooper escape from the cage, which allowed the footage to be used.<ref name=jawschap2>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"The Live Shark Footage\"}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|McBride|1999|pp=234\u2013235}}</ref> As production executive Bill Gilmore put it, \"The shark down in Australia rewrote the script and saved Dreyfuss's character.\"<ref>{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=235}}</ref>\n\nAlthough principal photography was scheduled to take 55 days, it did not [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrap]] until October 6, 1974, after 159 days.<ref name=\"Roan30Years\"/><ref name=\"McBride233\"/> Spielberg, reflecting on the protracted shoot, stated, \"I thought my career as a filmmaker was over. I heard rumors&nbsp;... that I would never work again because no one had ever taken a film 100 days over schedule.\"<ref name=\"Roan30Years\"/> Spielberg himself was not present for the shooting of the final scene in which the shark explodes, as he believed that the crew were planning to throw him in the water when the scene was done.<ref name=jawschap11/> It has since become a tradition for Spielberg to be absent when the final scene of one of his films is being shot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Richard Dreyfuss|url=http://www.sharkisstillworking.com/video2.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307073711/http://www.sharkisstillworking.com/video2.asp|publisher=[[The Shark Is Still Working]] official website|archivedate=March 7, 2008|accessdate=March 11, 2010}}</ref> Afterward, underwater scenes were shot at the [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] water tank in [[Culver City]], with stuntmen [[Dick Warlock]] and Frank James Sparks as stand-ins for Dreyfuss in the scene where the shark attacks the cage,<ref>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Finishing the Film\"}}</ref> as well as near [[Santa Catalina Island, California]]. Fields, who had completed a rough cut of the first two-thirds of the film, up until the shark hunt, finished the editing and reworked some of the material. According to Zanuck, \"She actually came in and reconstructed some scenes that Steven had constructed for comedy and made them terrifying, and some scenes he shot to be terrifying and made them comedy scenes.\"<ref name=McBride251>{{harvnb|McBride|1999|pages=251\u2013252}}</ref> The boat used for the ''Orca'' was brought to Los Angeles so the sound effects team could record sounds for both the ship and the underwater scenes.<ref name=Yewdall197>{{harvnb|Yewdall|2011|page=197}}</ref>\n\nTwo scenes were altered following test screenings. As the audience's screams had covered up Scheider's \"bigger boat\" one-liner, Brody's reaction after the shark jumps behind him was extended, and the volume of the line was raised.<ref name=Yewdall178>{{harvnb|Yewdall|2011|pages=178\u2013179}}</ref><ref name=Shone24>{{harvnb|Shone|2004|pages=24\u201325}}</ref> Spielberg also decided that he was greedy for \"one more scream\", and reshot the scene in which Hooper discovers Ben Gardner's body, using $3,000 of his own money after Universal refused to pay for the reshoot. The underwater scene was shot in Fields's swimming pool in [[Encino, Los Angeles|Encino, California]],<ref>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Sneak Previews\"}}</ref> using a [[Lifecasting|lifecast]] latex model of Craig Kingsbury's head attached to a fake body, which was placed in the wrecked boat's hull.<ref name=jawschap5/> To simulate the murky waters of Martha's Vineyard, powdered milk was poured into the pool, which was then covered with a [[tarpaulin]].<ref name=empire/>\n\n==Music==\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Main|Jaws (soundtrack)}}\n{{Listen| filename  = JawsJohnWilliams.ogg|title=\"Main Title and First Victim\"|description = The main theme for ''Jaws'', revolving around an [[ostinato]] of [[bass note]]s, which composer John Williams said were meant to represent the shark as an \"unstoppable force\" of \"mindless and instinctive attacks\"<ref name=jawschap14/>|pos=left}}\n[[John Williams]] composed the film's [[film score|score]], which earned him an [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Academy Award]] and was later ranked the sixth-greatest score by the [[American Film Institute]].<ref name=\"Oscars1976\"/><ref name=afiscores/> The main \"shark\" theme, a simple [[Double tonic|alternating pattern of two notes]]\u2014variously identified as \"E and F\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Matessino, Michael |work=[[Film Score Monthly]] |title=Letter in response to \"A Study of Jaws' Incisive Overture To Close Off the Century\" |url=http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/articles/1999/24_Sep---Film_Score_Friday.asp |date=September 24, 1999 |accessdate=December 17, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061017155301/http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/articles/1999/24_Sep---Film_Score_Friday.asp |archivedate=October 17, 2006}}</ref> or \"F and F sharp\"<ref name=Overture>{{cite news|author=Tylski, Alexandre |work=Film Score Monthly |title=A Study of Jaws' Incisive Overture To Close Off the Century |url=http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/articles/1999/14_Sep---A_Study_of_Jaws_Incisive_Overture.asp |accessdate=August 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061023150218/http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/articles/1999/14_Sep---A_Study_of_Jaws_Incisive_Overture.asp |archivedate=October 23, 2006}}</ref>\u2014became a classic piece of suspense music, synonymous with approaching danger (see [[leading-tone]]). Williams described the theme as \"grinding away at you, just as a shark would do, instinctual, relentless, unstoppable.\"<ref name=\"Friedman174\">{{harvnb|Friedman|2006|p=174}}</ref> The piece was performed by tuba player [[Tommy Johnson (tubist)|Tommy Johnson]]. When asked by Johnson why the melody was written in such a high register and not played by the more appropriate French horn, Williams responded that he wanted it to sound \"a little more threatening\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Chaundy, Bob |work=BBC News |title=Spies, sports, and sharks |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/6107576.stm|date=November 6, 2006 |accessdate=November 6, 2006}}</ref> When Williams first demonstrated his idea to Spielberg, playing just the two notes on a piano, Spielberg was said to have laughed, thinking that it was a joke. As Williams saw similarities between ''Jaws'' and pirate movies, at other points in the score he evoked \"pirate music\", which he called \"primal, but fun and entertaining\".<ref name=jawschap14>{{cite video|first=Laurent|last=Bouzereau|title=A Look Inside Jaws|location=''Jaws'': 30th Anniversary Edition DVD (2005)|year=1995|publisher=Universal Home Video|trans-title=\"Music by John Williams\"}}</ref> Calling for rapid, percussive string playing, the score contains echoes of ''[[La mer (Debussy)|La mer]]'' by [[Claude Debussy]] as well of [[Igor Stravinsky]]'s ''[[The Rite of Spring]]''.<ref name=Overture/><ref>{{Cite journal|title = John Williams and film music since 1971|journal = Popular Music and Society|date = March 1, 1997|issn = 0300-7766|pages = 59\u201372|volume = 21|issue = 1|doi = 10.1080/03007769708591655|first = Timothy E.|last = Scheurer}}</ref>\n\nThere are various interpretations of the meaning and effectiveness of the primary music theme, which is widely described as one of the most recognizable cinematic themes of all time.<ref name=\"Reelviews\">{{cite news | author=Berardinelli, James | publisher=Reelviews|year=2002|title=Jaws|url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/j/jaws.html| accessdate=August 6, 2006| author-link=James Berardinelli}}</ref> Music scholar Joseph Cancellaro proposes that the two-note expression mimics the shark's heartbeat.<ref>{{harvnb|Cancellaro|2006|p=170}}</ref> According to Alexandre Tylski, like themes [[Bernard Herrmann]] wrote for ''[[Taxi Driver]]'', ''[[North by Northwest]]'', and particularly ''[[Mysterious Island (1961 film)|Mysterious Island]]'', it suggests human respiration. He further argues that the score's strongest motif is actually \"the split, the rupture\"\u2014when it dramatically cuts off, as after Chrissie's death.<ref name=Overture/> The relationship between sound and silence is also taken advantage of in the way the audience is conditioned to associate the shark with its theme,<ref name=\"Friedman174\"/> which is exploited toward the film's climax when the shark suddenly appears with no musical introduction.<ref name=\"Reelviews\"/>\n\nSpielberg later said that without Williams's score the film would have been only half as successful, and according to Williams it jumpstarted his career.<ref name=jawschap14/> He had previously scored Spielberg's debut feature, ''The Sugarland Express'', and went on to collaborate with the director on almost all of his films.<ref name=\"Friedman174\"/> The [[Jaws (soundtrack)|original soundtrack for ''Jaws'']] was released by [[MCA Records]] on LP in 1975, and as a CD in 1992, including roughly a half hour of music that Williams redid for the album.<ref name=empirescore>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?SID=6144|title=Empire's Jaws Soundtrack Review|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|first=Ian|last=Freer|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref><ref name=decca/> In 2000, two versions of the score were released: [[Decca Records|Decca]]/[[Universal Music Group|Universal]] reissued the soundtrack album to coincide with the release of the 25th-anniversary DVD, featuring the entire 51 minutes of the original score,<ref name=empirescore/><ref name=decca>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031006122029/http://www.deccaclassics.com/music/soundtracks/jaws.html|title=Jaws \u2013 25th Anniversary Collector's Edition|publisher=[[Decca Classics]]|url=http://www.deccaclassics.com/music/soundtracks/jaws.html|archivedate=October 6, 2003|accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref> and [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]] put out a rerecording of the score performed by the [[Royal Scottish National Orchestra]], conducted by [[Joel McNeely]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.varesesarabande.com/servlet/the-614/Jaws/Detail|title=Jaws|publisher=[[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]]|accessdate=January 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427191725/http://www.varesesarabande.com/servlet/the-614/Jaws/Detail|archivedate=April 27, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\n\n===Influences===\n[[Herman Melville]]'s ''[[Moby-Dick]]'' is the most notable artistic antecedent to ''Jaws''. The character of Quint strongly resembles [[Ahab (Moby-Dick)|Captain Ahab]], the obsessed captain of the ''[[Pequod (Moby-Dick)|Pequod]]'' who devotes his life to hunting a [[sperm whale]]. Quint's monologue reveals a similar obsession with sharks; even his boat, the ''Orca'', is named after the only [[Orca|natural enemy of the white shark]]. In the novel and original screenplay, Quint dies after being dragged under the ocean by a harpoon tied to his leg, similar to the death of Ahab in Melville's novel.<ref>{{harvnb|Lemkin|1984|pp=277\u2013289}}</ref> A direct reference to these similarities may be found in Spielberg's draft of the screenplay, which introduces Quint watching the [[Moby Dick (1956 film)|film version of ''Moby-Dick'']]; his continuous laughter prompts other audience members to get up and leave the theater. However, the scene from ''Moby-Dick'' could not be licensed from the film's star, [[Gregory Peck]], its copyright holder.<ref name=jawschap1/> Screenwriter Carl Gottlieb also drew comparisons to [[Ernest Hemingway]]'s ''[[The Old Man and the Sea]]'': \"''Jaws'' is&nbsp;... a titanic struggle, like Melville or Hemingway.\"<ref name=baer209>{{harvnb|Baer|2008|page=209}}</ref>\n\nThe underwater scenes shot from the shark's point of view have been compared with passages in two 1950s horror films, ''[[Creature from the Black Lagoon]]'' and ''[[The Monster That Challenged the World]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Brosnan|1978|p=99}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Brosnan|1978|p=129}}</ref> Gottlieb named two science fiction productions from the same era as influences on how the shark was depicted, or not: ''[[The Thing from Another World]]'', which Gottlieb described as \"a great horror film where you only see the monster in the last reel\";<ref name=biskind290>{{harvnb|Biskind|1998|p=290}}</ref> and ''[[It Came From Outer Space]]'', where \"the suspense was built up because the creature was always off-camera\". Those precedents helped Spielberg and Gottlieb to \"concentrate on showing the 'effects' of the shark rather than the shark itself\".<ref name=Baer/> Scholars such as Thomas Schatz described how ''Jaws'' melds various genres while essentially being an [[action film]] and a [[thriller film|thriller]]. Most is taken from [[Horror fiction|horror]], with the core of a nature-based [[monster movie]] while adding elements of a [[slasher film]]. The second half provides a [[buddy film]] in the interaction between the crew of the ''Orca'', and a [[Supernatural horror film|supernatural horror]] based on the shark's depiction of a nearly Satanic menace.<ref>{{cite book |last=Schatz |first=Thomas |chapter=The New Hollywood |title=Movie Blockbusters |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6Q-OAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA25 25]}} In: {{harvnb|Stringer|2003|pp=15\u201344}}</ref> [[Ian Freer]] describes ''Jaws'' as an aquatic monster movie, citing the influence of earlier [[monster film]]s such as ''[[King Kong]]'' and ''[[Godzilla (franchise)|Godzilla]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Freer |first1=Ian |title=The Complete Spielberg |date=2001 |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |isbn=9780753505564 |page=[https://archive.org/details/completespielber0000free/page/48 48] |url=https://archive.org/details/completespielber0000free|url-access=registration }}</ref> Charles Derry, in 1977, also compared ''Jaws'' to ''Godzilla'';<ref>{{cite book |last1=Derry |first1=Charles |title=Dark Dreams: A Psychological History of the Modern Horror Film |date=1977 |publisher=A. S. Barnes |isbn=9780498019159 |page=[https://archive.org/details/darkdreamspsycho0000derr/page/82 82] |url=https://archive.org/details/darkdreamspsycho0000derr|url-access=registration }}</ref> and Spielberg cited ''[[Godzilla, King of the Monsters!]]'' (1956) as a formative influence growing up, due to the \"masterful\" way in which \"it made you believe it was really happening.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ryfle |first1=Steve |title=Japan's Favorite Mon-star: The Unauthorized Biography of \"The Big G\" |date=1998 |publisher=[[ECW Press]] |isbn=9781550223484 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/japansfavoritemo0000ryfl/page/15 15]\u201317 |url=https://archive.org/details/japansfavoritemo0000ryfl|url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nCritics such as Neil Sinyard have described similarities to [[Henrik Ibsen]]'s play ''[[An Enemy of the People]]''.<ref name=\"Sinyard32\">{{harvnb|Sinyard|1989|p=32}}</ref> Gottlieb himself said he and Spielberg referred to ''Jaws'' as \"''Moby-Dick'' meets ''Enemy of the People''\".<ref name=Baer208>{{harvnb|Baer|2008|p=208}}</ref> The Ibsen work features a doctor who discovers that a seaside town's medicinal hot springs, a major tourist attraction and revenue source, are contaminated. When the doctor attempts to convince the townspeople of the danger, he loses his job and is shunned. This plotline is paralleled in ''Jaws'' by Brody's conflict with Mayor Vaughn, who refuses to acknowledge the presence of a shark that may dissuade summer beachgoers from coming to Amity. Brody is vindicated when more shark attacks occur at the crowded beach in broad daylight. Sinyard calls the film a \"deft combination of Watergate and Ibsen's play\".<ref name=\"Sinyard32\"/>\n\n===Scholarly criticism===\n''Jaws'' has received attention from academic critics. Stephen Heath relates the film's ideological meanings to the then-recent [[Watergate scandal]]. He argues that Brody represents the \"white male middle class\u2014[there is] not a single black and, very quickly, not a single woman in the film\", who restores public order \"with an ordinary-guy kind of heroism born of fear-and-decency\".<ref>{{harvnb|Heath|1976|p=510}}</ref> Yet Heath moves beyond ideological content analysis to examine ''Jaws'' as a signal example of the film as \"industrial product\" that sells on the basis of \"the pleasure of cinema, thus yielding the perpetuation of the industry (which is why part of the meaning of ''Jaws'' is to be the most profitable movie)\".<ref>{{harvnb|Heath|1976|p=514}}</ref>\n\nAndrew Britton contrasts the film to the novel's post-Watergate cynicism, suggesting that its narrative alterations from the book (Hooper's survival, the shark's explosive death) help make it \"a communal exorcism, a ceremony for the restoration of ideological confidence.\" He suggests that the experience of the film is \"inconceivable\" without the mass audience's jubilation when the shark is annihilated, signifying the obliteration of evil itself.<ref>{{harvnb|Britton|1979|p=237}}</ref> In his view, Brody serves to demonstrate that \"individual action by the one just man is still a viable source for social change\".<ref name=Britton239>{{harvnb|Britton|1979|p=239}}</ref> [[Peter Biskind]] argues that the film does maintain post-Watergate cynicism concerning politics and politicians insofar as the sole villain beside the shark is the town's venal mayor. Yet he observes that, far from the narrative formulas so often employed by [[New Hollywood]] filmmakers of the era\u2014involving Us vs. Them, hip [[counterculture]] figures vs. \"[[The Man]]\"\u2014the overarching conflict in ''Jaws'' does not pit the heroes against authority figures, but against a menace that targets everyone regardless of socioeconomic position.<ref>{{harvnb|Biskind|1998|p=279}}</ref>\n\nWhereas Britton states that the film avoids the novel's theme of social class conflicts on Amity Island,<ref name=Britton239/> Biskind detects class divisions in the screen version and argues for their significance. \"Authority must be restored\", he writes, \"but not by Quint\". The seaman's \"working class toughness and bourgeois independence is alien and frightening&nbsp;... irrational and out of control\". Hooper, meanwhile, is \"associated with technology rather than experience, inherited wealth rather than self-made sufficiency\"; he is marginalized from the conclusive action, if less terminally than Quint.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Peter |last=Biskind |title=''Jaws'': Between the teeth |journal=[[Jump Cut (journal)|Jump Cut]] |pages=1\u201329 |year=1975|url=http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC09folder/Jaws.html |issue=9}}</ref> Britton sees the film more as concerned with the \"vulnerability of children and the need to protect and guard them\", which in turn helps generate a \"pervasive sense of the supreme value of family life: a value clearly related to [ideological] stability and cultural continuity\".<ref>{{harvnb|Britton|1979|p=238}}</ref>\n\n[[Fredric Jameson]]'s analysis highlights the [[polysemy]] of the shark and the multiple ways in which it can be and has been read\u2014from representing alien menaces such as communism or the Third World to more intimate dreads concerning the unreality of contemporary American life and the vain efforts to sanitize and suppress the knowledge of death. He asserts that its symbolic function is to be found in this very \"polysemousness which is profoundly ideological, insofar as it allows essentially social and historical anxieties to be folded back into apparently 'natural' ones&nbsp;... to be recontained in what looks like a conflict with other forms of biological existence.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Jameson|1979|pp=26\u201327}}</ref> He views Quint's demise as the symbolic overthrow of an old, populist, [[New Deal]] America and Brody and Hooper's partnership as an \"allegory of an alliance between the forces of law-and-order and the new technocracy of the multinational corporations&nbsp;... in which the viewer rejoices without understanding that he or she is excluded from it.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Jameson|1979|pp=28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n[[Neal Gabler]] analyzed the film as showing three different approaches to solving an obstacle: science (represented by Hooper), spiritualism (represented by Quint), and the common man (represented by Brody). The last of the three is the one which succeeds and is in that way endorsed by the film.<ref>{{cite news | first = Dan | last = Hagen | date = January 1988 | title = Neal Gabler | work = [[Comics Interview]] | issue = 54 | pages = 61\u201363 | publisher = [[Fictioneer Books]]}}</ref>\n\n===Audience emotional response===\nWhile in theaters, the film was said to have caused a single case of cinematic [[neurosis]] in a 17-year-old, female viewer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Robinson|first=J.A.|last2=Barnett|first2=A|date=1975|title=Letter: Jaws neurosis|url=|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=293|pages=1154\u20131155|via=Prime|doi=10.1056/NEJM197511272932224}}</ref> Cinematic neurosis is a condition in which viewers exhibit mental health disturbances, or a worsening of existing mental health disturbances, after viewing a film.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hamilton|first=James W.|date=1978|title=Cinematic Neurosis: A Brief Case Report|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Psychoanalysis|volume=6|issue=4|pages=569\u2013572|doi=10.1521/jaap.1.1978.6.4.569|pmid=689967|issn=0090-3604}}</ref> The symptoms first presented as sleep disturbances and anxiety, but one day later the patient was screaming \"Sharks! Sharks!\" and experiencing convulsions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ballon|first=Bruce|last2=Leszcz|first2=Molyn|date=2007|title=Horror Films: Tales to Master Terror or Shapers of Trauma?|journal=[[American Journal of Psychotherapy]]|language=en|volume=61|issue=2|pages=211\u2013230|doi=10.1176/appi.psychotherapy.2007.61.2.211|pmid=17760323|issn=0002-9564|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nThis case study caused the film to become notable in the medical community alongside ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'' for causing stress reactions in its viewers, and was later used in a study by Brian R. Johnson to test how susceptible audiences were to cinematic stress inducers.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnson|first=Brian R.|date=1980-12-01|title=General Occurrence of Stressful Reactions to Commercial Motion Pictures and Elements in Films Subjectively Identified as Stressors|journal=[[Psychological Reports]]|language=en|volume=47|issue=3|pages=775\u2013786|doi=10.2466/pr0.1980.47.3.775|pmid=7220719|issn=0033-2941}}</ref> His study found that stress could be induced by cinema in segments of the general population, and ''Jaws'' specifically caused stress reactions in its viewers. While Johnson could not find an exact cause for the stress response in viewers, whether it be the suspense, the gore or the music production, a 1986 study by G. Sparks found that particularly violent films, including ''Jaws'', tended to cause the most intense reactions in viewers.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CXT_AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA305&dq=jaws+1975+film+critical+response#v=onepage&q=jaws&f=false|title=Responding To the Screen: Reception and Reaction Processes|last=Bryant|first=Jennings|last2=Zillmann|first2=Dolf|date=2013-11-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136690914|pages=178|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Marketing===\nUniversal spent $1.8 million marketing ''Jaws'', including an unprecedented $700,000 on national television spot advertising.<ref name=\"SharkTale\">{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Neil|work=[[BBC]] News|title=Shark tale that changed Hollywood|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4600557.stm|date=June 3, 2005|accessdate=March 12, 2010}}</ref><ref name=mcbride255>{{harvnb|McBride|1999|pages=255\u2013256}}</ref> The media blitz included about two dozen 30-second advertisements airing each night on prime-time network TV between June 18, 1975, and the film's opening two days later.<ref name=\"Kochberg31\"/> Beyond that, in the description of film industry scholar Searle Kochberg, Universal \"devised and co-ordinated a highly innovative plan\" for the picture's marketing.<ref name=\"Kochberg31\"/> As early as October 1974, Zanuck, Brown, and Benchley hit the television and radio talk show circuit to promote the paperback edition of the novel and the forthcoming film.<ref>{{harvnb|Shone|2004|pp=26\u201327}}</ref> The studio and publisher Bantam agreed on a title logo that would appear on both the paperback and in all of the advertising for the film.<ref name=\"Kochberg31\"/> The centerpieces of the joint marketing strategy were John Williams's theme and the poster image featuring the shark approaching a lone female swimmer.<ref name=colrad>{{harvnb|Collins|Radner|1993|p=18}}</ref> The poster was based on the paperback's cover, and had the same artist, Bantam employee [[Roger Kastel]].<ref>{{harvnb|Petersen|1975|p=70}}</ref> The Seiniger Advertising agency spent six months designing the poster; principal Tony Seiniger explained that \"no matter what we did, it didn't look scary enough\". Seiniger ultimately decided that \"you had to actually go underneath the shark so you could see his teeth.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/media/2003-07-20-poster_x.htm|title=Poster king dreams up images to grab audiences|first=Bruce|last=Horovitz|work=[[USA Today]]|date=July 21, 2003|accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nMore merchandise was created to take advantage of the film's release. In 1999, Graeme Turner wrote that ''Jaws'' was accompanied by what was \"probably the most elaborate array of tie-ins\" including \"a sound-track album, T-shirts, plastic tumblers, a book about the making of the movie, the book the movie was based on, beach towels, blankets, shark costumes, toy sharks, hobby kits, iron-transfers, games, posters, shark's tooth necklaces, sleepwear, water pistols, and more.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Turner|1999|p=8}}</ref> The [[Ideal Toy Company]], for instance, produced a [[The Game of Jaws|game]] in which the player had to use a hook to fish out items from the shark's mouth before the jaws closed.<ref name=\"andrews115\">{{harvnb|Andrews|1999|p=115}}</ref>\n\n===Theatrical run===\nThe glowing audience response to a rough cut of the film at two test screenings in Dallas on March 26, 1975, and one in [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]], on March 28, along with the success of Benchley's novel and the early stages of Universal's marketing campaign, generated great interest among theater owners, facilitating the studio's plan to debut ''Jaws'' at hundreds of cinemas simultaneously.<ref>{{harvnb|Shone|2004|pp=23\u201326}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=253}}</ref> A third and final preview screening, of a cut incorporating changes inspired by the previous presentations, was held in Hollywood on April 24.<ref>{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=254}}</ref> After Universal chairman [[Lew Wasserman]] attended one of the screenings, he ordered the film's initial release \u2014 planned for a massive total of as many as 900 theaters \u2014 to be cut down, declaring, \"I want this picture to run all summer long. I don't want people in Palm Springs to see the picture in Palm Springs. I want them to have to get in their cars and drive to see it in Hollywood.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Shone|2004|p=26}}</ref> Nonetheless, the several hundred theaters that were still booked for the opening represented what was then an unusually [[wide release]]. At the time, wide openings were associated with movies of doubtful quality; not uncommon on the [[grindhouse]] and [[Exploitation film|exploitation]] side of the industry, they were customarily employed to diminish the effect of negative reviews and word of mouth. There had been some recent exceptions, including the rerelease of ''[[Billy Jack]]'' and the original release of its sequel ''[[The Trial of Billy Jack]]'', the ''[[Dirty Harry]]'' sequel ''[[Magnum Force]]'', and the latest installments in the [[James Bond in film|James Bond series]].<ref name=Wyatt111>{{harvnb|Wyatt|1994|p=111}}</ref><ref name=epics>{{harvnb|Hall|Neale|2010|pp=110\u2013112}}</ref> Still, the typical major studio [[film release]] at the time involved opening at a few big-city theaters, which allowed for a series of premieres. Distributors would then slowly forward prints to additional locales across the country, capitalizing on any positive critical or audience response. The outsized success of ''[[The Godfather]]'' in 1972 had sparked a trend toward wider releases, but even that film had debuted in just five theaters, before going wide in its second weekend.<ref name=pbs/>\n\nOn June 20, ''Jaws'' opened across North America on 464 screens \u2014 409 in the United States, the remainder in Canada.<ref name=HN108>{{harvnb|Hall|Neale|2010|p=108}}</ref> The coupling of this broad distribution pattern with the movie's then even rarer national television marketing campaign yielded a release method virtually unheard-of at the time.<ref name=Wyatt2>{{harvnb|Wyatt|1998|pp=78\u201379}}</ref> (A month earlier, [[Columbia Pictures]] had done something similar with a [[Charles Bronson]] thriller, ''[[Breakout (1975 film)|Breakout]]'', though that film's prospects for an extended run were much slimmer.)<ref>{{harvnb|Wyatt|1998|p=78}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Biskind|1998|p=277}}</ref> Universal president Sid Sheinberg reasoned that nationwide marketing costs would be amortized at a more favorable rate per print relative to a slow, scaled release.<ref name=Wyatt2/><ref>{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125104017/http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/may2006/nf20060522_1037.htm|archivedate=January 25, 2010 |url=http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/may2006/nf20060522_1037.htm |title=The Biggest Summer Blockbusters |first=Joseph |last=Pisani  |date=May 22, 2006 |work=[[Business Week]] |accessdate=September 20, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ayres|first=Alice|author2=Fordham, Alice|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article730585.ece|title=Man who gave summer blockbuster its bite dies |work=[[The Times]]|date=February 14, 2006|accessdate=March 12, 2010}}</ref> Building on the film's success, the release was subsequently expanded on July 25 to nearly 700 theaters, and on August 15 to more than 950.<ref>{{harvnb|Siska|1980|p=125}} This, the most detailed source, gives contradictory figures. The totals can variously be interpreted as 675 or 695 for July 25, and 954 or 974 for August 15.</ref> Overseas distribution followed the same pattern, with intensive television campaigns and wide releases \u2014 in Great Britain, for instance, ''Jaws'' opened in December at more than 100 theaters.<ref>{{harvnb|Wyatt|1998|p=79}}</ref>\n\nFor its fortieth anniversary, the film was released in selected theaters (across approximately 500 theaters) in the United States on Sunday, June 21, and Wednesday, June 24, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jaws-returning-theaters-40th-anniversary-798528|title='Jaws' Returning to Theaters for 40th Anniversary|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 28, 2015|accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20150528005082/en/%E2%80%98TCM-Presents%E2%80%99-Continues-JAWS-40th-Anniversary-Presentation/|title='TCM Presents' Continues with JAWS 40th Anniversary Presentation in Select U.S. Movie Theaters This June|work=[[Business Insider]]|date=May 28, 2015|accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Jaws'' opened in 409 theatres with a [[List of highest-grossing openings for films#Opening weekend record holders in a single territory|record]] $7 million weekend<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Murphy|first=A.D.|title='Deep' Opening a 52-year Col Peak at $8.1 mil |magazine=[[Variety (Magazine)|Variety]] |date=21 June 1977}}</ref> and grossed a record $21,116,354 in its first 10 days<ref name=BOMO>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jaws.htm|title=Jaws (1975)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=March 12, 2010}}</ref> recouping its production costs.{{sfn|Morris|2007|p=44}} It grossed $100 million in its first 59 days from 954 playdates.<ref>{{cite news |title=Showbusiness Headlines: Day-By-Day|magazine=[[Daily Variety]] |date=28 October 1975|page=87}}</ref> In just 78 days, it overtook ''The Godfather'' as the highest-grossing film at the North American box office,<ref name=pbs/> sailing past that picture's earnings of $86 million<ref name=Anderson/> and became the first film to earn $100 million in US [[Gross rental|theatrical rentals]].{{sfn|Hall|Neale|2010|p=210}} Its initial release ultimately brought in $123.1 million in rentals.{{sfn|Morris|2007|p=44}} Theatrical re-releases in 1976 and 1979 brought its total rentals to $133.4 million.<ref name=Anderson>{{cite news |last=Anderson |first=George |work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |title=Buffs Give Damn About 'Wind' Change |date=January 21, 1980 |page=[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=U55RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rG0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6868,2671819 24]}}</ref>\n\nThe picture entered overseas release in December 1975,<ref>{{cite news |author=Los Angeles (AP) |work=[[The Daytona Beach News-Journal]] |title='Jaws' Receipts Most in U.S. Film History |date=September 10, 1975 |page=[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ttAhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=\u201354FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1612,2834739 14A]}}</ref> and its international business mirrored its domestic performance. It broke records in Singapore,<ref>{{cite journal|title=\"Jaws\" breaks b.o. mark in Singapore|journal=Variety|issue=285|date=December 8, 1976|page=34}}</ref> New Zealand, Japan,<ref>{{cite journal|title=\"Jaws\" chomps into new b.o. marks at N. Zealand, Japan|journal=Variety|issue=281|date=January 28, 1976|page=33}}</ref> Spain,<ref>{{cite journal|title=\"Jaws\" in Spain: record $3.3-mil|journal=Variety|issue=282|date=February 18, 1976|page=3}}</ref> and Mexico.<ref>{{cite journal|title=\"Jaws\" openings break all Mexican records|journal=Box Office|issue=109|date=May 3, 1976|page=8}}</ref> On January 11, 1976, ''Jaws'' became the highest-grossing film worldwide with rentals of $132 million,  surpassing the $131 million earned by ''The Godfather''.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 21, 1976|page=102|title=Reprise As To 'Jaws'}}</ref> By the time of the third film in 1983, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that it had earned worldwide rentals of $270 million, from a gross of approximately $550 million.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Daily Variety]]|title=Film Reviews: Jaws 3-D|author=Loyn.|date=July 25, 1983|page=3}}</ref>\n\n''Jaws'' was the [[List of highest-grossing films|highest-grossing film of all time]] until ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'', which debuted two years later. ''Star Wars'' surpassed ''Jaws'' for the U.S. record six months after its release and set a new global record in 1978.<ref name=Fenner>{{cite news |last=Fenner |first=Pat. C. |work=[[Evening Independent]] |title=Independent Action |date=January 16, 1978 |page=[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JgAMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mVgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6721,49636 11\u2013A]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=New York (AP) |work=[[The StarPhoenix]] |title=Scariness of Jaws 2 unknown quantity |date=May 26, 1978 |page=[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TpZjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dnoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5679,3145694 21]}}</ref> Adjusted for inflation, ''Jaws'' has earned almost $2 billion worldwide at 2011 prices and is the second-most successful [[Media franchise|franchise]] film after ''Star Wars''.<ref>{{Cite news |author=The Economist online |date=July 11, 2011|title=Pottering on, and on \u2013 Highest-grossing film in franchise|work=[[The Economist]] |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/dailychart/2011/07/film-franchises |accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref> In North America, it is the [[List of highest-grossing films in Canada and the United States#Adjusted for ticket-price inflation|seventh-highest-grossing movie of all time]], with a total of $1.017 billion at current prices,<ref>{{cite web|website=Box Office Mojo |title=All Time Box Office Adjusted for Ticket Price Inflation |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/adjusted.htm |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> based on an estimated 128,078,800 tickets sold.<ref>{{cite web|website=Box Office Mojo |title=All Time Box Office Adjusted for Ticket Price Inflation:Est. Tickets |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/adjusted.htm?adjust_yr=1&p=.htm |accessdate=January 26, 2012}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, it is the seventh-highest-grossing film to be released since 1975, earning the equivalent of over \u00a370 million in 2009/10 currency,<ref>{{cite book |chapter=3.2 Inflation-adjusted top 20 films at the UK box office |title=Statistical Yearbook 2011 |year=2011 |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |chapter-url=http://statisticalyearbook11.ry.com/?id=82784 |accessdate=February 26, 2012 |page=24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120627131522/http://statisticalyearbook11.ry.com/?id=82784 |archivedate=June 27, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> with admissions estimated at 16.2 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Ultimate Chart: 1\u2013100 |year=2004 |publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100131090823/http://www.bfi.org.uk/features/ultimatefilm/chart/complete.php|archivedate=January 31, 2010|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/features/ultimatefilm/chart/complete.php |accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> ''Jaws'' has also sold 13 million tickets in Brazil, the second-highest attendance ever in the country behind ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://acervo2.folha.com.br/8/41/92/32/5329241/1024/5329241.jpg|title=Estudo confirma hegemonia dos EUA no cinema mundial|newspaper=[[Folha de S.Paulo]]|language=Portuguese|date=May 15, 2004|quote=The ten most viewed films in Brazil (million spectators) 1. ''Titanic'' (16.4) 2.''Jaws'' (13)}}</ref>\n\nOn television, the [[American Broadcasting Company]] aired it for the first time on November 4, 1979 right after its theatrical re-release.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[United States Patents Quarterly]]|volume=207|title=Universal City Studios, Inc. v. Montgomery Ward & Co., Inc|year=1980|issue=851}}</ref> The first U.S. broadcast received a [[Nielsen rating]] of 39.1 and attracted 57 percent of the total audience, the second-highest televised movie audience at the time behind ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' and the fourth-highest rated.<ref>{{cite news|author=Brown, Les|title=\"Jaws\" played to 80 million on ABC|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 7, 1979|page=C29}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Hit Movies on U.S. TV Since 1961|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 24, 1990|page=160}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, 23 million people watched its inaugural broadcast in October 1981, the [[List of most-watched television broadcasts|second-biggest TV audience ever for a feature film]] behind ''[[Live and Let Die (film)|Live and Let Die]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.corrie.net/chat/ratucs/press/top100.html |title=TV's jewels fail to shine in list of all-time winners |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=February 7, 1998 |accessdate=May 4, 2011|first=Alison|last=Boshoff}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''Jaws'' received mostly positive reviews upon release.<ref>{{harvnb|Moritz|1978|p=402}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=55193|title=Detail view of movies: Jaws|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called it \"a sensationally effective action picture, a scary thriller that works all the better because it's populated with characters that have been developed into human beings\".<ref>{{cite news| author=Ebert, Roger | title=Jaws | work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19750101/REVIEWS/501010332/1023| date=January 1, 1975| accessdate = August 3, 2006}}</ref> [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']]'s A. D. Murphy praised Spielberg's directorial skills, and called Robert Shaw's performance \"absolutely magnificent\".<ref>{{cite news| author=Murphy, A. D. | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|title=Jaws |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117792123/| date=June 18, 1975| accessdate=August 3, 2006}}</ref> According to ''[[The New Yorker]]''{{'}}s [[Pauline Kael]], it was \"the most cheerfully perverse scare movie ever made&nbsp;... [with] more zest than an early [[Woody Allen]] picture, a lot more electricity, [and] it's funny in a Woody Allen sort of way\".<ref>{{harvnb|Kael|1976|pp=195\u2013196}}</ref> For ''[[New Times (magazine)|New Times]]'' magazine, [[Frank Rich]] wrote, \"Spielberg is blessed with a talent that is absurdly absent from most American filmmakers these days: this man actually knows how to tell a story on screen.&nbsp;... It speaks well of this director's gifts that some of the most frightening sequences in ''Jaws'' are those where we don't even see the shark.\"<ref name=\"McBride256\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=256}}</ref> Writing for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, [[Judith Crist]] described the film as \"an exhilarating adventure entertainment of the highest order\" and complimented its acting and \"extraordinary technical achievements\".<ref>{{cite news| author=Crist, Judith | work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|title=Fish Story On a Grand Scale|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1-gCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA69| date=June 23, 1975| accessdate=August 3, 2006}}</ref> [[Rex Reed]] praised the \"nerve-frying\" action scenes and concluded that \"for the most part, ''Jaws'' is a gripping horror film that works beautifully in every department\".<ref>{{cite news  |first = Rex|last = Reed |title = Film to Jaw About: 'Le Chat's' Meow | work=[[New York Daily News]]|date = June 15, 1975}}</ref>\n\nThe film was not without its detractors. [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"It's a measure of how the film operates that not once do we feel particular sympathy for any of the shark's victims.&nbsp;... In the best films, characters are revealed in terms of the action. In movies like ''Jaws'', characters are simply functions of the action&nbsp;... like stage hands who move props around and deliver information when it's necessary\". He did, however, describe it as \"the sort of nonsense that can be a good deal of fun\".<ref>{{cite news| last=Canby |first=Vincent| work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Entrapped by 'Jaws' of Fear|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/06/21/movies/moviesspecial/21JAWS.html| date=June 21, 1975| accessdate=August 3, 2006}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' critic [[Charles Champlin]] disagreed with the film's PG rating, saying that \"''Jaws'' is too gruesome for children, and likely to turn the stomach of the impressionable at any age.&nbsp;... It is a coarse-grained and exploitative work which depends on excess for its impact. Ashore it is a bore, awkwardly staged and lumpily written.\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Champlin | first=Charles | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | title=Don't Go Near the Water |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/herocomplex/la-et-hc-jaws-original-review-20150619-story.html| date=June 20, 1975| accessdate=August 31, 2006}}</ref> Marcia Magill of ''[[National Board of Review of Motion Pictures|Films in Review]]'' said that while ''Jaws'' \"is eminently worth seeing for its second half\", she felt that before the protagonists' pursuit of the shark the film was \"often flawed by its busyness\".<ref name=fir>{{cite journal|title=Jaws|journal=[[National Board of Review of Motion Pictures|Films in Review]]|date=August\u2013September 1975|page=436|first=Marcia|last=Magill}}</ref> William S. Pechter of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'' described ''Jaws'' as \"a mind-numbing repast for sense-sated gluttons\" and \"filmmaking of this essentially manipulative sort\"; Molly Haskell of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' similarly characterized it as a \"scare machine that works with computer-like precision.&nbsp;... You feel like a rat, being given shock therapy\".<ref name=\"McBride256\"/> The most frequently criticized aspect of the film has been the artificiality of its mechanical antagonist: Magill declared that \"the programmed shark has one truly phony close-up\",<ref name=fir/> and in 2002, online reviewer [[James Berardinelli]] said that if not for Spielberg's deftly suspenseful direction, \"we would be doubled over with laughter at the cheesiness of the animatronic creature.\"<ref name=\"Reelviews\"/> ''[[Halliwell's Film Guide]]'' stated that \"despite genuinely suspenseful and frightening sequences, it is a slackly narrated and sometimes flatly handled thriller with an over-abundance of dialogue and, when it finally appears, a pretty unconvincing monster.\"<ref>''Halliwell's Film Guide'', 13th edition \u2013 {{ISBN|0-00-638868-X}}.</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''Jaws'' won three [[Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]], [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Dramatic Score]], and [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound]] ([[Robert Hoyt (sound engineer)|Robert Hoyt]], [[Roger Heman Jr|Roger Heman]], [[Earl Madery]], and [[John Carter (sound engineer)|John Carter]]).<ref name=\"Oscars1976\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1976 |title=The 48th Academy Awards (1976) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=October 2, 2011|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Morris45\">{{harvnb|Morris|2007|p=45}}</ref> It was also nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], losing to ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (film)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]''.<ref name=\"McBride257\">{{harvnb|McBride|1999|p=257}}</ref> Spielberg greatly resented the fact that he was not nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]].<ref name=\"McBride256\"/> Along with the Oscar, John Williams's score won the [[Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media|Grammy Award]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=&title=Jaws&year=All&genre=All|title=Past Winners Search|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref> the [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music]],<ref name=bafta/> and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Golden Globe Award]].<ref name=globes/> To her Academy Award, Verna Fields added the [[American Cinema Editors]]' Eddie Award for Best Edited Feature Film.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050319062147/http://www.eonline.com/On/Holly/Shows/Jaws/factsheet.html|archivedate=March 19, 2005|url=http://www.eonline.com/On/Holly/Shows/Jaws/factsheet.html|title=Fact Sheet: Jaws|publisher=E! Entertainment Television|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Jaws'' was chosen Favorite Movie at the [[People's Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.peopleschoice.com/v/26949318/and-the-2nd-annual-favorite-movie-people-s-choice-is-jaws.htm|title=And the 2nd Annual \"Favorite Movie People's Choice\" is&nbsp;... Jaws!|publisher=[[People's Choice Awards]]|accessdate=January 5, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725112719/http://search.peopleschoice.com/v/26949318/and-the-2nd-annual-favorite-movie-people-s-choice-is-jaws.htm|archivedate=July 25, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was also nominated for best Film, Director, Actor (Richard Dreyfuss), Editing, and Sound at the [[29th British Academy Film Awards]],<ref name=bafta>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards-database.html?&year=1975|title=Film Nominations 1975|publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]]|accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> and Best Film\u2014Drama, Director, and Screenplay at the [[33rd Golden Globe Awards]].<ref name=globes>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/year/1975 |title=33rd Annual Golden Globe Awards Nominations |publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124174412/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/year/1975 |archivedate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> Spielberg was nominated by the [[Directors Guild of America]] for a [[Directors Guild of America Award|DGA Award]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dga.org/Awards/History/1970s/1975.aspx|title=Awards / History / 1975 \u2013 28th Annual DGA Awards|publisher=[[Directors Guild of America]]|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref> and the [[Writers Guild of America, West|Writers Guild of America]] nominated Peter Benchley and Carl Gottlieb's script for [[Writers Guild of America Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Drama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://librarycatalog.wgfoundation.org/title/titleAwards.ashx?id=806 |title=Writers Guild Foundation Library Catalog: Jaws |publisher=[[Writers Guild of America, West]] |accessdate=January 5, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618201645/http://librarycatalog.wgfoundation.org/title/titleAwards.ashx?id=806 |archivedate=June 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the years since its release, ''Jaws'' has frequently been cited by film critics and industry professionals as one of [[List of films considered the best|the greatest movies of all time]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_all1000films_table.php |title=1,000 Greatest Films (Full List) |accessdate=January 10, 2016}} \"102. Jaws - Spielberg, Steven (1975)</ref> It was number 48 on American Film Institute's ''[[AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Movies|100 Years ... 100 Movies]]'', a list of the greatest American films of all time compiled in 1998; it dropped to number 56 on the [[AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition)|10-Year Anniversary list]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afi.com/100years/movies10.aspx|title=AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Movies \u2013 10th Anniversary Edition|publisher=American Film Institute|accessdate=January 3, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602034514/http://www.afi.com/100years/movies10.aspx|archive-date=June 2, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/100years/movies10.aspx |title=AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition) |publisher=American Film Institute|accessdate= August 17, 2010}}</ref> AFI also ranked the shark at number 18 on its list of the [[AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Heroes & Villains|50 Best Villains]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/100years/handv.aspx |title=AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Heroes & Villains |publisher=American Film Institute|accessdate= August 17, 2010}}</ref> Roy Scheider's line \"You're gonna need a bigger boat\" 35th on a list of [[AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Movie Quotes|top 100 movie quotes]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/100years/quotes.aspx |title=AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Quotes |publisher=American Film Institute|accessdate= August 17, 2010}}</ref> Williams's score at sixth on a list of [[AFI's 100 Years of Film Scores|100 Years of Film Scores]],<ref name=afiscores>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/100years/scores.aspx|title=AFI's 100 YEARS OF FILM SCORES|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref> and the film as second on a list of [[AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Thrills|100 most thrilling films]], behind only ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/100Years/thrills.aspx|title=AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Thrills|publisher=American Film Institute|accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref> In 2003, ''The New York Times'' included the film on its list of the best 1,000 movies ever made.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/ref/movies/1000best.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | title=The Best 1,000 Movies Ever Made | date=April 29, 2003 | accessdate= July 4, 2010}}</ref> The following year, ''Jaws'' placed at the top of the [[Bravo (U.S. TV network)|Bravo]] network's five-hour miniseries ''[[The 100 Scariest Movie Moments]]''.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bravotv.com/The_100_Scariest_Movie_Moments/index.shtml| title = The 100 Scariest Movie Moments: 100 Scariest Moments in Movie History\u2014Official Bravo TV Site| accessdate = July 28, 2010 | year = 2004 | publisher = [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo Company]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071030070540/http://www.bravotv.com/The_100_Scariest_Movie_Moments/index.shtml| archivedate = October 30, 2007<!-- 07:05:40 -->}}</ref> The [[Chicago Film Critics Association]] named it the sixth-scariest film ever made in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205025611/http://chicagofilmcritics.org/|url=http://chicagofilmcritics.org/|title=CFCA's 100 Scariest Movies of All Time|publisher=[[Chicago Film Critics Association]] |archivedate=December 5, 2006 |accessdate= July 2, 2010}}</ref> In 2008, ''Jaws'' was ranked the fifth-greatest film in history by ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine,<ref name=\"Empire5\">{{cite news|authors=Simon Braund, Glen Ferris, Ian Freer, Nev Pierce, Chris Hewitt, Dan Jolin, Ian Nathan, Kim Newman, Helen O'Hara, Olly Richards, and Owen Willams|work=Empire|title=The 500 Greatest Movies of All Time|url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/95.asp|accessdate=March 11, 2010}}</ref> which also placed Quint at number 50 on its list of the 100 Greatest Movie Characters of All Time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=50 |title=''Empire's'' The 100 Greatest Movie Characters |work=Empire |accessdate=May 21, 2010}}</ref> The film has been cited in many other lists of 50 and 100 greatest films, including ones compiled by [[Leonard Maltin]],<ref>{{harvnb|Maltin|1999|p=13}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'',<ref>{{harvnb|Burr|1999|page=52}}</ref> ''[[Film4]]'',<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Film4]] |url=http://www.filmsite.org/filmfour.html |title=Film Four's 100 Greatest Films of All Time |publisher=Published by [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] [[Filmsite.org|FilmSite.org]] |accessdate= August 17, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://www.filmsite.org/rstone.html |title= 100 Maverick Movies|author=Travers, Peter|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=December 1999|issue=830/831 |accessdate= January 15, 2011|author-link= Peter Travers}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/100-greatest-movies-of-all-time/page:6 |title=Total Film features: 100 Greatest Movies Of All Time |magazine=[[Total Film]] |date=January 25, 2010 |accessdate= August 17, 2010}}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[TV Guide]]|date=August 8\u201314, 1998|url=http://www.filmsite.org/tvguide.html |title=50 Greatest Movies (on TV and Video)|pages=14\u201333|accessdate= January 15, 2011}}</ref> and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/films/50greatestfilms |title= 50 Greatest Films|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=September 2005 |accessdate= January 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, the United States Library of Congress selected it for preservation in the [[National Film Registry]], recognizing it as a landmark horror film and the first \"summer movie\".<ref name=\"2001Add\">{{cite press release|title=Librarian of Congress Names 25 More Films to National Film Registry |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |date=December 18, 2001 |url=https://www.loc.gov/film/nfr2001.html |accessdate=March 11, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207100732/http://www.loc.gov/film/nfr2001.html |archivedate=December 7, 2009}}</ref> In 2006, its screenplay was ranked the 63rd-best of all time by the [[Writers Guild of America]].<ref name=Screenplay>{{cite web|title=101 Best Screenplays |date=April 7, 2006 |publisher=[[Writers Guild of America, West]] |url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |accessdate=July 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813151310/http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |archivedate=August 13, 2006}}</ref> In 2012, the [[Motion Picture Editors Guild]] listed the film as the eighth best-edited film of all time based on a survey of its membership.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The 75 Best Edited Films |journal=Editors Guild Magazine |date=May 2012 |volume=1 |issue=3 |url=https://www.editorsguild.com/magazine.cfm?ArticleID=1102}}</ref>\n\n===Legacy===\n[[File:UniversalStudiosJawsSharkCloseup.JPG|thumb|upright|alt=A large replica of the film's shark hangs from a wooden frame. A sign next to it says \"Jaws\" and a man standing nearby is about a third of the height of the shark. A pulley and rope are used to pretend to hold the shark's mouth open.|The entrance of the now closed [[Jaws (ride)|''Jaws'' ride]] at [[Universal Studios Florida]]]]\n''Jaws'' was key in establishing the benefits of a wide national release backed by heavy television advertising, rather than the traditional progressive release in which a film slowly entered new markets and built support over time.<ref name=\"Kochberg31\">{{harvnb|Kochberg|1996|p=31}}</ref><ref name=pbs>{{cite web | work=[[PBS]]|year=2001| title=Jaws\u2013The Monster That Ate Hollywood |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/hollywood/business/jaws.html| accessdate=August 6, 2006}}</ref> Saturation booking, in which a film opens simultaneously at thousands of cinemas, and massive media buys are now commonplace for the [[major film studio|major Hollywood studios]].<ref>{{harvnb|Marich|2005|p=79}}</ref> According to [[Peter Biskind]], ''Jaws'' \"diminish[ed] the importance of print reviews, making it virtually impossible for a film to build slowly, finding its audience by dint of mere quality. ... Moreover, ''Jaws'' whet corporate appetites for big profits quickly, which is to say, studios wanted every film to be ''Jaws''.\"<ref name=Biskind278>{{harvnb|Biskind|1998|p=278}}</ref> Scholar Thomas Schatz writes that it \"recalibrated the profit potential of the Hollywood hit, and redefined its status as a marketable commodity and cultural phenomenon as well. The film brought an emphatic end to Hollywood's five-year recession, while ushering in an era of high-cost, high-tech, high-speed thrillers.\"<ref name=Friedman176>{{harvnb|Friedman|2006|p=176}}</ref>\n\n''Jaws'' also played a major part in establishing summer as the prime season for the release of studios' biggest box-office contenders, their intended [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbusters]];<ref name=pbs/><ref>{{cite news|work=BBC News|title=Rise of the Blockbuster|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1653733.stm|date=November 16, 2001|accessdate=March 12, 2010}}</ref> winter had long been the time when most hoped-for hits were distributed, while summer was largely reserved for dumping films thought likely to be poor performers.<ref name=Friedman176/> ''Jaws'' and ''Star Wars'' are regarded as marking the beginning of the new [[Cinema of the United States|U.S. film industry]] business model dominated by \"[[high-concept]]\" pictures \u2014 with premises that can be easily described and marketed \u2014 as well as the beginning of the end of the New Hollywood period, which saw [[auteur]] films increasingly disregarded in favor of profitable big-budget pictures.<ref name=pbs/><ref name=\"Wyatt 21\">{{harvnb|Wyatt|1994|p=21}}</ref> The New Hollywood era was defined by the relative autonomy filmmakers were able to attain within the major studio system; in Biskind's description, \"Spielberg was the [[Trojan Horse|Trojan horse]] through which the studios began to reassert their power.\"<ref name=Biskind278/>\n\nThe film had broader cultural repercussions, as well. Similar to the way the pivotal scene in 1960's ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' made showers a new source of anxiety, ''Jaws'' led many viewers to fear going into the ocean.<ref name=\"Gordon33\">{{harvnb|Gordon|2008|p=33}}</ref><ref name=\"Jackson23\">{{harvnb|Jackson|2007|p=23}}</ref> Reduced beach attendance in 1975 was attributed to it,<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/jaws-launched-summer-blockbuster-35-years-ago/story?id=10855868|date=June 18, 2010|publisher=[[ABC News]]|title=Jaws' Launched Summer Blockbuster 35 Years Ago|first=Luchina|last=Fisher|accessdate=January 14, 2011}}</ref> as well as an increased number of reported shark sightings.<ref>{{harvnb|Siska|1980|p=131}}</ref> It is still seen as responsible for perpetuating negative stereotypes about sharks and their behavior,<ref name=\"NGSharks\">{{cite news|last=Lovgren|first=Stefan|work=[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]|title=\"Jaws\" at 30: Film Stoked Fear, Study of Great White Sharks|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2005/06/0615_050615_jawssharks.html|date=June 15, 2005|accessdate=March 12, 2010}}</ref> and for producing the so-called \"''Jaws'' effect\", which allegedly inspired \"legions of fishermen [who] piled into boats and killed thousands of the ocean predators in shark-fishing tournaments.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Fleshler, David |work=[[Sun Sentinel]] |title=One-third of world's sharks, skates and rays face extinction |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2010-10-31/news/fl-endangered-sharks-20101030_1_nurse-shark-bull-shark-tiger-sharks|date=October 31, 2010|accessdate=January 11, 2010}}</ref> Benchley stated that he would not have written the original novel had he known what sharks are really like in the wild.<ref>{{cite news |author=Metcalf, Geoff |publisher=geoffmetcalf.com |title=Great white shark, the fragile giant |url=http://www.geoffmetcalf.com/qa/19634.html|accessdate=August 4, 2006|author-link=Geoff Metcalf }}</ref> Conservation groups have bemoaned the fact that the film has made it considerably harder to convince the public that sharks should be protected.<ref>{{cite news|author=Chapple, Mike |work=[[Liverpool Daily Post]] |title=Great white hope|page=3|url=http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/entertainment/previewsandreviews/tm_objectid=15919800%26method=full%26siteid=50061%26page=3%26headline=great%2dwhite%2dhope-name_page.html|date=September 1, 2005|accessdate=March 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Jaws'' set the template for many subsequent horror films, to the extent that the script for [[Ridley Scott]]'s 1979 science fiction film ''[[Alien (film)|Alien]]'' was pitched to studio executives as \"''Jaws'' in space\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Hays |first=Matthew |work=[[Montreal Mirror]] |title=A Space Odyssey |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605192429/http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2003/102303/film1.html |archivedate=June 5, 2011 |url=http://www.montrealmirror.com/ARCHIVES/2003/102303/film1.html|accessdate=July 31, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Ochoa|2011|p=135}}</ref> Many films based on man-eating animals, usually aquatic, were released through the 1970s and 1980s, such as ''[[Orca (film)|Orca]]'', ''[[Grizzly (film)|Grizzly]]'', ''[[Mako: The Jaws of Death]]'', ''[[Barracuda (1978 film)|Barracuda]]'', ''[[Alligator (film)|Alligator]]'', ''[[Day of the Animals]]'', ''[[Tintorera]]'', and ''[[Eaten Alive]]''. Spielberg declared ''[[Piranha (1978 film)|Piranha]]'', directed by [[Joe Dante]] and written by [[John Sayles]], \"the best of the ''Jaws'' ripoffs\".<ref name=\"McBride257\"/> Among the various foreign [[mockbuster]]s based on ''Jaws'', three came from Italy: ''[[Great White (film)|Great White]]'',<ref name=Stanley220>{{harvnb|Stanley|1988|p=220}}</ref> which inspired a plagiarism lawsuit by Universal and was even marketed in some countries as a part of the ''Jaws'' franchise;<ref>{{harvnb|Adamson|Morrison|2011|p=80}}</ref> ''[[Monster Shark]]'',<ref name=Stanley220/> featured in ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' under the title ''Devil Fish'';<ref>''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' Series 9 Episode 11 \u2013 first broadcast August 15, 1998</ref> and ''[[Deep Blood]]'', which blends in a supernatural element.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/deep-blood-v312947/review|title=Deep Blood (1990)|publisher=[[Allrovi]]|first=Jeremy|last=Wheeler|accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref> The 2009 Japanese horror film ''Psycho Shark'' was released in the United States as ''[[Jaws in Japan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://io9.com/5637161/jaws-in-japan-promises-cyclopean-selachimorphae-breasts|title=\"Jaws in Japan\" promises cyclopean Selachimorphae, breasts|author=Lamar, Cyriaque|date=September 13, 2010|publisher=Jabootu's Bad Movie Dimension| accessdate=July 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\nRichard Dreyfuss made a cameo appearance in the 2010 film ''[[Piranha 3D]]'', a loose remake of the 1978 film. Dreyfuss plays Matt Boyd, a fisherman who is the first victim of the title creatures. Dreyfuss later stated that his character was a parody and a near-reincarnation of Matt Hooper, his character in ''Jaws''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodnews.com/2010/05/05/richard-dreyfuss-reveals-why-he-made-%E2%80%98piranha-3-d%E2%80%99-%E2%80%9Cto-get-money%E2%80%9D/|title=Richard Dreyfuss reveals why he made 'Piranha 3-D:' \"to get money\";\u2013 Film.com|accessdate=August 19, 2010|publisher=Film.com}}</ref> During his appearance, Dreyfuss's character listens to the song \"[[Show Me the Way to Go Home]]\" on the radio, which Hooper, Quint and Brody sing together aboard the ''Orca''.\n\nMartha's Vineyard celebrated the film's 30th anniversary in 2005 with a \"JawsFest\" festival,<ref name=jawsfest/> which had a second edition in 2012.<ref name=jf2>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.vulture.com/2012/08/jaws-blu-ray-jawfest-marthas-vineyard.html|title=Jaws Fanatics Gather to Pray to God of Sharks|first=Rachel|last=Kramer Bussel|date=August 15, 2012|magazine=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|accessdate=January 4, 2013}}</ref> An independent group of fans produced the feature-length documentary ''[[The Shark Is Still Working]]'', featuring interviews with the film's cast and crew. Narrated by Roy Scheider and dedicated to Peter Benchley, who died in 2006, it debuted at the 2009 Los Angeles United Film Festival.<ref>{{cite web |title=First look: 'The Shark is Still Working' |publisher=Los Angeles United Film Festival|url=http://losangelesunitedfest.bside.com/2009/films/thesharkisstillworking_losangelesunitedfest2009|first=Erik |last=Hollander |accessdate=January 1, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417001335/http://losangelesunitedfest.bside.com/2009/films/thesharkisstillworking_losangelesunitedfest2009|archivedate=April 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Shark is Still Working official website|url=http://www.sharkisstillworking.com/ |archivedate=August 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811122940/http://www.sharkisstillworking.com/|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, 2020, it was announced that [[Donna Feore]] will direct and choreograph \u201cBruce,\u201d the musical retelling of the behind-the-scenes story of Jaws, with Richard Oberacker writing the musical book and lyrics and Robert Taylor working on the music and is set to premiere from June to July 2021 at the Paper Mill Playhouse in [[Millburn, New Jersey]].<ref>{{Cite web|first=Greg|last=Evans|title=\u2018Jaws\u2019-Themed Stage Musical \u2018Bruce\u2019 Swimming Toward Summer 2021|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/jaws-stage-musical-bruce-paper-mill-playhouse-carl-gottlieb-steven-spielberg-1202891156/|date=March 24, 2020|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe first ever [[LaserDisc]] title marketed in [[North America]] was the MCA [[DiscoVision]] release of ''Jaws'' in 1978.<ref>{{harvnb|Mast|Kawin|2003|page=198}}</ref> A second LaserDisc was released in 1992,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QRIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA65|page=65|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|title=LaserScans|first=Chris|last=McGowan|accessdate=January 1, 2012|date=July 7, 1992}}</ref> before a third and final version came out under MCA/Universal Home Video's Signature Collection imprint in 1995. This release was an elaborate box-set that included deleted scenes and outtakes, a new two-hour documentary on the making of the film directed and produced by Laurent Bouzereau, a copy of the novel ''Jaws'', and a CD of the soundtrack by John Williams.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA62|journal=Billboard|title=LaserDisk Karaoke: In Titles|first=Chris|last=McGowan|accessdate=January 1, 2012|date=March 23, 1996|pages=62\u201363}}</ref>\n\nMCA Home Video first released ''Jaws'' on VHS in 1980.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HSQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT64|page=64|journal=Billboard |title=Video Shark|accessdate=January 1, 2012|date=July 26, 1980|last1=Nielsen Business Media|first1=Inc}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Bowker|1994|page=419}}</ref> For the film's 20th anniversary in 1995, MCA Universal Home Video issued a new Collector's Edition tape featuring a making-of retrospective.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,299824,00.html|title=Jaws (1995)|first=Chris|last=Nashawaty|work=Entertainment Weekly |date=December 1, 1995|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref> This release sold 800,000 units in North America.<ref name=billdvd>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA132 |page=132|journal=Billboard|title=Spielberg Releases 'Jaws' on DVD as Universal Marks Shark's 25th Anniversary|first=Eileen|last=Fitzpatrick|accessdate=January 1, 2012|date=May 13, 2000}}</ref> Another, final VHS release, marking the film's 25th anniversary in 2000, came with a companion tape containing a documentary, deleted scenes, outtakes, and a trailer.<ref>{{cite web |work=Los Angeles Times|first=Susan|last=King|date=July 13, 2000|title=Feeding 'Jaws' Fans|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/jul/13/entertainment/ca-51986|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Jaws'' was first released on DVD in 2000 for the film's 25th anniversary, accompanied by a massive publicity campaign.<ref name=billdvd /> It featured a 50-minute documentary on the making of the film (an edited version of that featured on the 1995 LaserDisc release), with interviews with Spielberg, Scheider, Dreyfuss, Benchley, and other cast and crew members. Other extras included deleted scenes, outtakes, trailers, production photos, and storyboards.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jaws: 25th Anniversary Edition |url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/037/037280p1.html |website=[[IGN]]|first=Matt|last=Venendaal |date=July 11, 2000|accessdate=April 15, 2010}}</ref> The DVD shipped one million copies in just one month.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA85|page=85 |journal=Billboard|title=Universal 'Jaws' DVD Ships One Million Plus; Spinal Tap Seeks Drummer Through Listen.com|first=Eileen|last=Fitzpatrick |accessdate=January 1, 2012|date=August 5, 2000}}</ref> In June 2005, a 30th anniversary edition was released at the JawsFest festival on Martha's Vineyard.<ref name=jawsfest>{{cite web |work=Los Angeles Times|first=Elaine|last=Dutka|date=June 14, 2005|title=Making this cold fish hot again|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/jun/14/entertainment/et-dvd14 |accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref> The new DVD had many extras seen in previous home video releases, including the full two-hour Bouzereau documentary, and a previously unavailable interview with Spielberg conducted on the set of ''Jaws'' in 1974.<ref name=30thdvd>{{cite web |url=http://www.totalfilm.com/reviews/dvd/jaws |title=Jaws (12) |work=Total Film |date=August 29, 2005|accessdate=April 15, 2010}}</ref> On the second JawsFest in August 2012, the [[Blu-ray]] Disc of ''Jaws'' was released,<ref name=jf2/> with over four hours of extras, including ''The Shark Is Still Working''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collider.com/jaws-blu-ray-release-date-trailer/158175/?_r=true|title=Universal Confirms Digitally Remastered JAWS Coming to Blu-ray August 14; Watch Steven Spielberg Talk About the Restoration |website=Collider|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|date=April 10, 2012|accessdate=April 11, 2012}}</ref> The Blu-ray release was part of the celebrations of Universal's 100th anniversary, and debuted at fourth place in the charts, with over 362,000 units sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homemediamagazine.com/top-sellers/hunger-games-sweeps-sales-and-rental-charts-28145|work=[[Home Media Magazine]]|title='Hunger Games' Sweeps Sales and Rental Charts|date=August 22, 2012|accessdate=March 9, 2013|first=Thomas K.|last=Arnold|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220220906/http://www.homemediamagazine.com/top-sellers/hunger-games-sweeps-sales-and-rental-charts-28145|archivedate=December 20, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The film will be released on 4K Ultra HD on June 2nd, 2020.<ref>{{Citation|title=Jaws 4K Blu-ray|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=26655|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n\n===Adaptations and merchandise===\nThe film has inspired two [[Jaws (ride)|theme park rides]]: one at [[Universal Studios Florida]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Jaws |publisher=[[Universal Studios Florida|Universal Orlando]] |url=http://www.universalorlando.com/Theme_Parks/Universal_Studios_Orlando/Attractions/jaws_ride.aspx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010151811/http://www.universalorlando.com/Theme_Parks/Universal_Studios_Orlando/Attractions/jaws_ride.aspx|archivedate=October 10, 2009 |accessdate=January 2, 2012}}</ref> which closed in January 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2012-01-02/business/os-universal-studios-jaws-closes-20120102_1_mechanical-sharks-wizarding-world-universal-studios|title=It's the end of the line for Jaws at Universal|first=Dewayne|last=Bevil|date=January 2, 2012|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|accessdate=January 3, 2012}}</ref> and one at [[Universal Studios Japan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jaws |publisher=[[Universal Studios Japan|Universal Japan]] |url=http://www.usj.co.jp/e/attraction/jaws.html |accessdate=April 15, 2010}}</ref> There is also an animatronic version of a scene from the film on the [[Studio Tour]] at [[Universal Studios Hollywood]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universalstudioshollywood.com/attractions/studio-tour |series=attractions |title=Studio Tour |publisher=universalstudioshollywood.com |access-date=July 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613121739/http://www.universalstudioshollywood.com/attractions/studio-tour/ |archive-date=June 13, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There have been at least two musical adaptations: ''JAWS The Musical!'', which premiered in 2004 at the Minnesota Fringe Festival, and ''[[Giant Killer Shark: The Musical]]'', which premiered in 2006 at the [[Toronto Fringe Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Giant Killer Shark And Other Meta-Musicals |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070620114513/http://music.aol.ca/article/giant_killer_shark/2/|archivedate=June 20, 2007|url=http://music.aol.ca/article/giant_killer_shark/2/ |first=Sam |last=Sutherland |date=May 2, 2007|work=[[AOL]] Music |accessdate=April 15, 2010}}</ref> Three video games based on the film were released: 1987's ''[[Jaws (video game)|Jaws]]'', developed by [[List of Acclaim Entertainment subsidiaries|LJN]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/jaws-1987|title=Jaws (1987)|website=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref> 2006's ''[[Jaws Unleashed]]'' by [[Majesco Entertainment]] for the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[PlayStation 2]], and [[Personal computer game|PC]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/709/709698p1.html|title=JAWS Ships Out|date=May 23, 2006|website=IGN|first=Jeremy|last=Dunham|accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref> and 2011's ''Jaws: Ultimate Predator'', also by Majesco, for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] and [[Wii]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/jaws-ultimate-predator-chomping-wii-3ds-6316710|date=June 2, 2011|title=Jaws: Ultimate Predator chomping Wii, 3DS|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|website=GameSpot|accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref> A [[mobile game]] was released in 2010 for the [[iPhone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wireless.ign.com/articles/111/1114451p1.html|title=Jaws Surfaces on the iTunes App Store|date=August 19, 2006|website=IGN|accessdate=January 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113121018/http://wireless.ign.com/articles/111/1114451p1.html|archivedate=January 13, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Aristocrat made an officially licensed slot machine based on the movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aristocrat.com.au/company/Media%20Room/080509%20Aristocrats%20newest%20Hyperlink%20Slot%20JAWS%20makes%20world%20premiere%20at%20Sycuan%20Casino.pdf|title=Aristocrat's newest Hyperlink Slot, JAWS\u2122 makes world premiere at Sycuan Casino|publisher=Aristocrat|date=May 8, 2009|accessdate=September 15, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130827105355/http://www.aristocrat.com.au/company/Media%20Room/080509%20Aristocrats%20newest%20Hyperlink%20Slot%20JAWS%20makes%20world%20premiere%20at%20Sycuan%20Casino.pdf|archivedate=August 27, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2017, video game developer [[Zen Studios]] developed and released a virtual pinball adaptation of the film as part of the Universal Classics add-on pack for the virtual pinball game ''[[Pinball FX 3]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Good |first1=Owen |title=Pinball FX3 has big names lining up for a table |url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/8/26/16208556/pinball-fx3-universal-classics-preview-zen-studios |website=Polygon |accessdate=21 November 2019 |date=26 August 2017}}</ref> This table features 3-D figures of Quint and Jaws, with the opportunity to play missions from either character's perspective.\n\n==Sequels==\n''Jaws'' spawned three sequels to declining critical favor and commercial performance. Their combined domestic grosses amount to barely half of the first film's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=jaws.htm|title=Jaws Movies|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=March 12, 2010}}</ref> In October 1975, Spielberg declared to a film festival audience that \"making a sequel to anything is just a cheap carny trick\".<ref name=\"McBride257\"/> Nonetheless, he did consider taking on the first sequel when its original director, [[John D. Hancock]], was fired a few days into the shoot; ultimately, his obligations to ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'', which he was working on with Dreyfuss, made it impossible.<ref>{{harvnb|McBride|1999|pages=257\u2013258}}</ref> ''[[Jaws 2]]'' (1978) was eventually directed by [[Jeannot Szwarc]]; Scheider, Gary, Hamilton, and [[Jeffrey Kramer]] all reprised their roles. It is generally regarded as the best of the sequels.<ref>\n* {{harvnb|Muir|2007|p=555}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?fid=133463|title=Jaws 2|work=Empire|first=Mark|last=Dinning |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018194753/https://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?fid=133463|accessdate=January 5, 2012 |archivedate=October 18, 2014}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/200/200170p1.html|title=Jaws 2 \u2013 DVD Review|website=IGN|date=May 15, 2001|first=Nick|last=Nunziata|accessdate=January 5, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Jaws 3-D]]'' (1983) does not feature any of the original actors, although it was directed by Joe Alves, who had served as art director and production designer, respectively, on the two preceding films.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Joe Alves and Jaws 3-D|journal=[[Fangoria]]|date=August 1979|page=29|issue=1}}</ref> Starring [[Dennis Quaid]] and [[Louis Gossett Jr.]], it was released to heavily negative reviews in [[3-D film|3-D]] format. However, the effect did not transfer to television or home video, where it was renamed ''Jaws 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/08/20/pirahna-3d-jaws-3d/|title=Introducing the PopWatch Rewind! Week 1: 'Jaws 3-D'|date=August 20, 2010|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=January 4, 2012|author1=Franich, Darren |author2=Staskiewicz, Keith }}</ref> ''[[Jaws: The Revenge]]'' (1987), directed by [[Joseph Sargent]], starring [[Michael Caine]], and featuring the return of Gary, is considered one of the [[List of films considered the worst|worst movies ever made]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Nashawaty|first=Chris|title=The 25 Worst Sequels Ever Made \u2013 10. Jaws: The Revenge (1987) |work=Entertainment Weekly|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1169126_17,00.html|accessdate=March 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1987 Archive |work=[[Golden Raspberry Awards]] |url=http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=27 |accessdate=December 11, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140501200426/http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=27 |archivedate=May 1, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> While all three sequels made a profit at the box office (''Jaws 2'' and ''Jaws 3-D'' were among the top 20 highest-grossing films of their respective years), critics and audiences alike were largely dissatisfied with the films.<ref>\n* {{cite web |title=Jaws 3-D |work=Variety |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117792125?refcatid=31|date=January 1, 1983 |accessdate=November 28, 2006}}\n* {{cite news |first=Tse|last=Derek|title=Sequels we wish we'd missed |work=[[The London Free Press]] |url=http://www.canoe.ca/NewsStand/LondonFreePress/Today/2003/06/10/107674.html|date=June 10, 2003|accessdate=March 11, 2010}}\n* {{cite news |first=Caryn |last=James |title=Film: 'Jaws the Revenge,' The Fourth in the Series |work=The New York Times |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0DEFDB133CF93BA25754C0A961948260|date=July 18, 1987 |accessdate=June 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|Speculative fiction/Horror|Sharks}}\n* [[List of American films of 1975]]\n*[[List of natural horror films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|33em}}\n* {{cite book|title=Law for Business and Personal Use|last1=Adamson|first1=John E.|last2=Morrison|first2=Amanda|publisher=[[Cengage Learning]]|location=Stamford, Connecticut|year=2011|isbn=978-0-538-49690-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Nigel|year=1999 |title=Nigel Andrews on Jaws |publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|location=London|isbn=978-0-7475-3975-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Baer|first=William|title=Classic American Films: Conversations with the Screenwriters|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood]]|location=Westport, Connecticut|year=2008|isbn=978-0-313-34898-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Biskind|